<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, June 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indonesian Quake Kills at Least 44
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A powerful earthquake and several strong
aftershocks rocked the Indonesian island of Sumatra, leaving at least 44 dead
and thousands homeless, authorities said Monday. The Indonesian Meteorological
and Geophysical Service said the quake, measuring magnitude 7.3, was centered
beneath the Indian Ocean, about 400 miles northwest of Jakarta and 60 east of
Bengkulu, a city of about 1.2 million. The death toll was expected to rise. In
Western Japan, a moderate earthquake with a preliminary magnitude of 4.7 hit
Monday morning, but there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Solomon Islands Premier Taken Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- A rebel group fighting in the Solomon Islands
took the prime minister and other government officials hostage Monday and put up
road blocks around the capital, officials in New Zealand said. The rebels were
demanding that Prime Minister Bartholemew Ulufa'alua resign within 48 hours,
said Brad Pattersfield, the spokesman for New Zealand's Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and Trade. He said it was unclear where Bartholemew and the other
government members were being held, or what had motivated the apparent coup
attempt.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OAS Launches Annual Assembly
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- As hundreds of anti-free trade protesters chanted
outside, foreign ministers from the Organization of American States launched
their annual assembly Sunday, expecting to focus on Peru's presidential
election. Police arrested 41 people -- 35 of whom were among 200 who mobbed a
bus containing three OAS delegates and a driver, according to Staff Sgt. Dave
Rossell of the Windsor Police Service. Protesters chanted and wagged their
fingers at the police officers, who in turn rapped nightsticks on riot shields
to move the crowd back.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Horn of Africa Peace Talks Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Ethiopia reportedly issued new demands for
international peacekeepers Sunday as it resumed indirect talks with Eritrea to
resolve a two-year border war. The talks included ''serious discussion'' on
security issues, including an Ethiopian army redeployment and use of
international observers and troops in the Horn of Africa, a Western diplomat
said on condition of anonymity. Ethiopia's premier said his country would
withdraw from Eritrean territory if international peacekeepers were based in
lands it now occupies, the state-owned Ethiopian Herald reported Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Romanians Vote in Local Elections
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP)-- Exit polls from local elections showed Sunday the
party of former President Ion Iliescu leading in the capital Bucharest for the
first time in eight years. The local elections, in which financial unrest and
disillusionment with politicians kept many voters away, were considered
significant as a measure of political power in advance of parliamentary and
presidential elections later this year. Polls show Iliescu favored to defeat
President Emil Constantinescu in the presidential contest.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Copehagen' Named Best Play At Tonys
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Copenhagen'' was chosen best play and '''Kiss Me, Kate,''
best musical revival Sunday, as Michael Blakemore scored a Tony first -- winning
the awards for his direction of both. Susan Stroman, whose musical ''Contact,''
a daring dance play that pushes musical-theater boundaries, won the award for
best choreography. Elton John and Tim Rice picked up the award for best score
for their pop retelling of ''Aida.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands Mourn Tito Puente
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Saddened fans and fellow musicians lined up at a Manhattan
funeral chapel Sunday to bid a fond farewell to their beloved El Rey, mambo king
Tito Puente. Mourners held Puerto Rican flags, wore T-shirts emblazoned with his
image and listened to his music while trading memories of the flamboyant
percussionist and bandleader outside Riverside Chapel. Puente, a famed timbale
player, died Wednesday at age 77.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks surged Monday. The Nikkei rose 403.03 points to
17,203.09 at the end of morning trading.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Murder Charges Dropped Against Ray Lewis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- An attorney for Baltimore Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis said
Sunday night that a deal had been struck and the murder charges against him will
be dropped and he will plead guilty to a misdemeanor charge of obstruction of
justice. Don Samuel, one of Lewis' attorneys, confirmed to The Associated Press
that Lewis would not do any jail time and receive a maximum term of 12 months'
probation under first offender status.
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
