<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressTed Graber:
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. (AP) -- Ted Graber, the Beverly Hills interior
designer who refurbished the White House family quarters for first
lady Nancy Reagan, died Saturday. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   He died in an assisted living facility from complications of
Alzheimer's disease, said his assistant of 45 years, Jean Mathison.
</P>
<P>
   Graber received attention in the 1980s when he directed a
massive remodeling of the White House living quarters for Nancy
Reagan. After the Reagans returned to Los Angeles, Graber remodeled
their Bel-Air home and the president's Century City office.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Los Angeles, Graber began his career in 1945, with
clients that included Alfred and Betsy Bloomingdale, Walter and Lee
Annenberg and, from Hollywood, Joan Crawford, Jack and Mary Benny,
and Jack Warner.
</P>
<P>
   He was known for combining modern, comfortable furniture with
antiques and wood floors to create stylish interiors.
</P>
<P>
   Graber retired to Northern California in 1989.
Julian Osborne:
</P>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Julian ''Ozzie'' Osborne, a columnist for
The Miami Herald, shot himself to death a day after quitting his
job, police said. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, who wrote about life in the Keys, died Saturday in a
Key West hospital. He shot himself late Friday with a .22-caliber
handgun while he stood on the Riviera Canal Bridge, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We at the Herald are deeply saddened,'' said Martin Baron, the
newspaper's executive editor. ''Ozzie made wonderful contributions
over the years to this newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and colleagues said he was depressed over leaving his
20-hour-a-week job at the newspaper's Key West bureau. He quit
after he was asked to write six columns a week instead of four.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Osborne wrote a note to his editors apologizing for
resigning on short notice and said he needed to tend to family
business in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne worked at the Herald for 13 years. His column, ''Over
the Fence,'' appeared on Sunday mornings. He reported on ordinary
''Conchs,'' as Keys residents are known locally, to famous
underwater treasure hunters, such as the late Mel Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   His last signed column, published a week ago, profiled an artist
who teaches young children.
</P>
<P>
   A regular vacationer to the Cayman Islands, Osborne ended up in
Key West due to a reservations mix-up. He enjoyed the color of the
island city so much he moved there permanently in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two nephews.
Robert Cochrane:
</P>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) -- Robert B. Cochrane, a former Baltimore Sun
war correspondent who covered the Japanese surrender concluding
World War II, has died. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Cochrane died May 29 of bone cancer, his family said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He originally covered the Navy when the war began but was later
assigned by the Sun to the Pacific theater. He was one of 200
journalists to witness the Japanese formally surrender during a
22-minute ceremony aboard the USS Missouri anchored in Tokyo Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The story was included in ''Masterpieces of World War II
Reporting,'' a 1962 book that included stories by Ernie Pyle,
Edward R. Murrow, Walter Cronkite and Ernest Hemmingway.
</P>
<P>
   Born Dec. 3, 1909, in Asheville, N.C., he began his career at
The Asheville Citizen. After graduating from Duke University, he
worked for the Durham (N.C.) Herald before moving to the Sun in
1934.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Cochrane opened the Sun's Tokyo bureau. In 1946,
he became the first employee of WMAR-TV, which was owned by the
Sun. Cochrane retired in 1975 as the station's programming director
and moved to Florida 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Juanita Shockley Reichard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 0128 </TRAILER>
