<DOCNO> APW20000605.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Poet Comforts Civil War Wounded  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The poet moved slowly through the hospital
wards, a large, gray-bearded man dressed in gray with a
broad-brimmed hat and a kindly, affectionate air.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Whitman was more a visitor than a nurse, offering his
attention to the wounded and sick from a dozen Civil War
battlefields, listening to stories of the war from Union soldiers
who were little more than boys. Passing out small gifts: a sheet of
writing paper, a postage stamp, an orange, a piece of candy, a
cigar. He wrote letters home for those who could not write
themselves, took messages from dying men for mothers, wives and
sweethearts.
</P>
<P>
   ''His presence seemed to light up the place,'' a friend
remembered. When he turned to leave, the voices called out, ''Walt!
Walt! Walt! Come again! Come again!''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman was 43, author of the ever-changing, controversial and
groundbreaking ''Leaves of Grass'' and a former Brooklyn, N.Y.,
newspaper editor when his mission among the casualties of war began
with a family quest.
</P>
<P>
   The New York newspapers had listed his brother, George Whitman,
as among the wounded at the battle of Fredericksburg in Virginia
and Whitman went south in search of him.
</P>
<P>
   His brother was not seriously hurt, but Whitman was asked to
accompany other injured men back to the hospitals at Washington and
found his life had changed.
</P>
<P>
   The poet found work as a government clerk to sustain himself and
began the hospital visits that were to last for most of three
years. At war's end he estimated that he had made ''over 600 visits
or tours and went ... among from 80,000 to 100,000 of the wounded
and sick, as sustainer of spirit and body ... in time of need.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the war, Washington saw the establishment at
least 56 hospitals set up in camps and barracks, private homes,
churches, the arsenal, hotels, warehouses, the city hall, the U.S.
Patent Office and for a time, the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman recalled that some hastily built hospitals sprawled
building after building until they appeared about the size of a
small town, if one could imagine a town that held only ''wounds,
sickness and death.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin G. Murray, writing in Washington History, the journal of
the Historical Society of Washington, D.C., said Whitman spoke with
admiration of the doctors and nurses with ''everything bent to save
a life from the very grip of the destroyer.''
</P>
<P>
   But the art of war was far more advanced than the art of
medicine in the first half of the 1860s and many of the patients
Whitman visited were dying.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of 1865, more than 18,000 soldiers had died in
Washington hospitals, with many succumbing to disease, Murray
reports. The city's newspapers gave partial statistics: Deaths due
to gunshot wounds, 3,421; typhoid fever, 2,255, chronic diarrhea,
1,370; and amputation, 560.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's attention to the young men in the hospital wards, many
of whom he kissed, did not please all of the medical personnel; one
nurse called him ''odious.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chief surgeon of one of the largest hospitals later
offered this testimonial in an unsuccessful attempt to win Whitman
a government pension: ''I am of (the) opinion that no one person
who assisted in the hospitals during the war accomplished so much
good for the soldier and for the government as Mr. Whitman.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, of course, was a professional writer and the war and
the wounded, the city and its people, sustained his prose and
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ''Drumtaps,'' published in 1865, contained battlefield and
campground poetry and the moving odes to Abraham Lincoln: ''When
Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloomed'' and ''O Captain, My
Captain.'' They were later folded into ''Leaves of Grass.''
Whitman's war experiences also resulted in ''Memorandum During the
War,'' ''Specimen Days'' and a volume of letters, ''The
Wound-Dresser.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's sentry-guarded house on a wintry night was to
Whitman ''the White House of future poems, and dreams and dramas.''
Lit by a flooding moon etching the shadows of tree limbs on its
white walls, it was a place ''full of reality, full of illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Whitman's description of the marbled, tall-ceilinged
rooms of the Patent Office, recently a hospital for ''the worst
wounded of the war,'' but now swept clean and decorated for
Lincoln's 1865 inaugural ball:
</P>
<P>
   ''To-night, beautiful women, perfumes, the violin's sweetness,
the polka and the waltz; then the amputation, the blue face, the
groan, the glassy eye of the dying, the clotted rag, the odor of
wounds and blood, and many a mother's son amid strangers, passing
away untended there ... and much for nurse to do, and much for
surgeon.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on the White
House, Congress and the history of Washington for more than 30
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
