<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denver Grandparents Help Military  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WELLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Don't tell Betty and Joe Tinianow about the
military's manpower problem. They've just contributed three
grandchildren to the officer corps.
</P>
<P>
   Not grandsons Brandon, Jeffrey or Ryan. The new second
lieutenants are Natalie, Tracy and Casey -- their granddaughters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just find that a sign of the times. None of the boys wanted
to go,'' said Betty. Five of the top ten graduates this year at the
Air Force Academy were women.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy was first, Casey sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think women are showing that they have the ability to do as
well or better in many fields, especially intellectual and
leadership fields, as men,'' said Betty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if I will live to see it but I believe there will
be a woman president,'' said Joe, 76, whose parents fled Russia
during the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   While twins Tracy and Casey, both 21, were graduating at the top
of their class, Natalie, 22, managed to graduate with her class at
West Point despite blowing a knee on an obstacle course. She has a
screw in the injured knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went to both graduations,'' said Betty. Natalie is the
daughter of the Tinianows' daughter, Gerri. The twins are the
daughters of the Tinianows' son, Albert.
</P>
<P>
   The twins have always been precocious and Betty wasn't surprised
by their performance. ''They are in competition with each other all
the time. I thought Natalie did miraculously just to keep up with
the class and graduate after her surgery,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the Tinianows' first contribution to the military. Son
Albert is a colonel and in charge of logistics for the Air Force
Space Command in Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Joe was in the artillery in World War II. ''The only women
around were nurses.'' He soon married Betty, a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Betty said the grandparents were able to keep a close eye on
Natalie because she lived nearby. ''When she was in 10th or 11th
grade she said she wanted to go into the military.
</P>
<P>
   ''The twins came down from Montana (where their father was
stationed) about a year later and said they had seen a recruiter.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty said both twins knew the hardships of a military life, and
that it would mean the first real separation in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the time they poked their noses out they were Air Force
brats, and they knew what they were getting into,'' said Betty.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Air Force has been wonderful to us. We've grown up in the
Air Force, and the people are just phenomenal,'' said Casey on
graduation day last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being a woman is no different than being a man here,'' added
Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, Albert, said, ''I think they wish they could start
serving right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Separated into different squadrons at the academy, the twins
will be back together this fall. The Air Force is sending them to
Northwestern University to become doctors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 0149 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000605.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes Missile Defense Plan  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Telling Russians they need not fear American
missile defense efforts, President Clinton went to their parliament
as well as their president with his message of support for
strengthening democratic rule and the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was addressing the Duma, the Russian parliament, before
his goodbye call on Putin. Then he was to fly on to Kiev, Ukraine,
before returning to Washington late tonight.
</P>
<P>
   In a summit statement Sunday, issued in the gilded splendor of
St. George's Hall in the Kremlin, the two presidents agreed there
is ''a dangerous and growing threat'' of nuclear missile strikes
from states outside the lines of world order. They called it a
potentially significant change in the strategic situation.
</P>
<P>
   But they did not agree on what to do about it. ''We're against
having a cure which is worse than the disease,'' Putin said at a
quick, summit-ending news conference -- two questions to each
president.
</P>
<P>
   It ended a long day's deliberations on arms control, economics,
global warming, terrorism and crime. Clinton and Putin conferred
first for well over an hour with only one aide apiece, then U.S.
and Russian delegations met at a long, blonde maple conference
table in St. Catherine's Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said afterward that he and Clinton had established good
business ties as well as personal relations. ''For me, President
Clinton is a person who is a very comfortable and pleasant partner
in negotiations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one heard them calling each other Bill and Vladimir as in the
backslapping days of Boris Yeltsin, Putin's sponsor and
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   But there was room for some banter, as when Clinton pointed out
the three monkey pins climbing the shoulder of Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's jacket. They represented an American saying,
''Hear no evil, see no evil, speak no evil,'' Clinton said.
''That's Madeleine's whole foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   His aim at the summit was to make the most of agreements set
before he and Putin discussed the hard points without settling
them. Clinton said even that was a good thing, ''the candor and
clarity of our disagreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin said efforts to solve the differences would continue when
they meet at three international conferences later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the accords they did sign:
</P>
<P>
   --One to reduce the weapons-grade plutonium stockpiles of each
nation by 34 tons, a 20-year plan that will cost billions. The
United States will spend $200 million to help Russia get started,
and the administration is seeking international funding to keep it
going.
</P>
<P>
   --Another to establish an early warning center in Moscow, from
which U.S. and Russian military experts will exchange information
within minutes on the launching of ballistic missiles or space
vehicles detected by either nation.
</P>
<P>
   The deal covers only launchings that might intrude on Russian or
U.S. territory. It is supposed to reduce the danger that missiles
might be launched because of false warnings of an attack.
</P>
<P>
   They also signed a joint statement on strategic stability,
urging final approval of the START II nuclear arms reduction treaty
by the Senate -- where Republicans may balk at a term-ending
achievement for Clinton -- and looking toward a START III deal.
</P>
<P>
   But there were differences there, too. The START III blueprint
is for reductions on each side to between 2,000 and 2,500 nuclear
warheads, 1,000 fewer than in START II, which isn't in effect yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians want the follow-on treaty to cut weapons to 1,500
apiece, but Clinton said ''it would require us to change our
strategic plan and should be left for future negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The impasse on a proposed U.S. missile defense system was more
sharply etched. A limited system is being tested, and Clinton may
order it started, to guard against future attacks from rogue states
-- North Korea and Iraq are the two cited as possible threats.
</P>
<P>
   That would require changes in the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
treaty, and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said Putin
made ''absolutely clear'' that Russia opposed them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he does not want to breach the ABM treaty, but he
did not state flatly that the United States would not exercise its
right to withdraw from the pact.
</P>
<P>
   On a Moscow radio call-in program Sunday night, interviewer
Aleksey Venediktov asked Clinton why he wouldn't accept Putin's
suggestion that they cooperate on a different kind of missile
defense. It would seek to down missiles soon after they are
launched, instead of trying to intercept them in space, which the
ABM treaty forbids.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is, we think it will take 10 years or more to
develop'' that kind of system, Clinton said. ''We expect to face
this threat in the United States within five years,'' when he said
the space-intercept system could be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it frightens Russians, obviously,'' Venediktov said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton replied: ''Yes, I understand, but I think they wouldn't
be frightened if they understand the exact nature of the
difference. ... If the U.S. has a missile defense that can stop a
couple of missiles from North Korea, does it have the potential to
upset what has kept us safe all these years, which is mutual
deterrence? We say no, the Russians say it might. So we're trying
to work that through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
