<HEADLINE> Presidential Primary Season Ending  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY MASSEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- By the time Stephen Flance draws back the
curtain of a voting machine in New Mexico's presidential primary,
it will be too late to help the candidate of his choice -- three
months too late.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico is one of five states quietly bringing the primary
season to an end on Tuesday. Democrat Al Gore and Republican George
W. Bush clinched their nominations in early March -- before half the
states even voted.
</P>
<P>
   Flance, a Santa Fe real estate agent, supported Democrat Bill
Bradley and is none too happy to have his vote rendered meaningless
in the nominating process. Bradley quit the race after March's
Super Tuesday contests.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could have had a very timely impact on the presidential
race if this primary had been in February or early March. But once
again we find ourselves behind the curve and out of the action,''
Flance said.
</P>
<P>
   Also holding presidential primaries are Alabama, Montana, New
Jersey and South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Flance plans to vote Tuesday because he's interested in state
and local races: Congretainly low for Kentucky's primary two weeks ago.
Only 14 percent of registered Democrats and 11 percent of
Republicans voted.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is traditionally the presidential contest that draws people
to the polls, whether it's a primary or general election,'' said F.
Chris Garcia, a political science professor at the University of
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   George ''Jeep'' Gilliland, head of the New Mexico Federation of
Labor, said simply, ''We're out of the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature rejected last year a proposal to move up the
date of the state's presidential primary to avert exactly what's
happening -- a primary with no presidential contest and only local
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The state Democratic and Republican parties have left primary
election turnout efforts -- such as telephone banks -- to local
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Gore and Bush campaigns in New Mexico already
have turned their attention to the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush visited Albuquerque last week, holding fund-raisers and
speaking on national defense matters at a rally that drew about 500
people. But not once at the rally did Bush appeal to people to turn
out for Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was in Albuquerque in late April. The 300 invited guests at
a town meeting were ''undecided'' voters -- Democrats, Republicans
and independents who will be needed to win in November.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a Gore spokesman, said the campaign relies on
volunteers rather than mailings or advertising to reach voters in
the late primary states such as New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big country and a long campaign. We save money where we
can and make the best use of volunteers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Look on Gore's campaign Web site for information about New
Mexico and there's no mention of Tuesday's primary. There is a
reminder of the voter registration deadline for the November
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Only New Mexicans registered as Democrats, Republicans or Green
Party voters can cast ballots in their respective primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 9,000 Greens account for roughly 1 percent of
statewide registration.
</P>
<P>
   Although the late presidential primaries may not matter, Garcia
said there's a strong chance that New Mexico, with its five
electoral votes, will receive more attention from the presidential
candidates as the general election nears.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico is among six Western states that have swung between
Republican and Democratic nominees in the past three elections.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.gore2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
