<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Honors WWII Veterans  </HEADLINE>
By BRETT MARTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Before time does what enemy fire could not,
America's living World War II veterans will at last see their
triumphant legacy enshrined in a major national event.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of America, Tuesday's opening of the National D-Day
Museum could allay more than a half century of festering guilt over
the fact that something similar hadn't been done earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's way overdue,'' said veteran Bob Slaughter, 75, of
Roanoke, Va., who took a bullet across his head and shrapnel in his
back over the course of numerous battles from Normandy to central
Europe. ''I kept thinking somebody's going to do this, and they
just didn't. The war was becoming forgotten and school children
didn't know anything about it, and it just wasn't fair to the guys
still over there in those graves.''
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 6 million of the more than 16 million people who
served in the military during World War II are alive. Their average
age is 77, and they're dying at a rate of about 1,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's opening ceremonies will bring together an estimated
10,000 World War II veterans, the largest gathering since the war
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The D-Day Museum, founded by historian and best-selling author
Stephen Ambrose, will examine the entire war, with special
attention dedicated to the New Orleans-built, shoe box-shaped
landing boats used in every D-Day invasion in Europe and the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose speculates that America lagged in national monuments or
museums dedicated to the war in part because those who fought found
the experience so horrific they avoided reliving it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Veterans didn't want to talk about that war,'' said Ambrose,
who researched two best-selling books on the subject. ''Now they've
reached an age where they're beginning to leave us, and we better
get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   In his drive to recount the tales of horror and heroism, Ambrose
found veterans generous in donating items to bring those stories to
life.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in a 70,500-square-foot renovated structure in the city's
gentrified warehouse district, the museum combines about 5,000
artifacts with oral histories, posters, props, video and animation
to create a vivid history of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nearly every artifact has a story connected to it, whether it
be a hole in a helmet or a belt that a medic carried around with
him as he treated the wounded on the beach,'' Ambrose said.
</P>
<P>
   Oral history booths feature veteran accounts of the war as a TV
screen fades in and out of related still photos, many showing the
storytellers as they looked during the war.
</P>
<P>
   One main theater and three smaller ones will showcase combat and
other war footage, eventually including rare color footage shot by
military cameramen who caught everything from the bloodstained
decks of a landing craft at Normandy to jubilant Parisians lining
the streets as the allies liberated the city from the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Audio descriptions of war strategies and troop movements are
illustrated by animated maps, beamed from ceiling projectors onto
white oval floor screens.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is far more grand than the $1 million project Ambrose
envisioned 15 years ago near the University of New Orleans campus,
where he once taught and museum chairman Nick Mueller still does.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose had simply run out of room to keep artifacts he
collected in his research. He found fund raising difficult until he
widened the scope to include those who fought in the Pacific and
North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pacific wing opens in August 2001, the final price tag
is expected to be $25 million, Mueller said. The federal government
has given $6 million, while Louisiana contributed $6.7 million. The
rest came from private donors.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the museum became the leading national project
commemorating the war effort, Ambrose still felt New Orleans was
the right place for it, in part because he wanted to emphasize the
role of the late Andrew Jackson Higgins, a local shipbuilder whose
36-foot troop transports brought invading troops ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Dwight D. Eisenhower, who chose Ambrose as his
biographer, credited Higgins with winning the war by making it
possible to invade onto an open beach.
</P>
<P>
   Below a pair of fighter planes hanging from the ceiling of the
main pavilion will sit a working replica of Higgins' landing craft.
Researchers failed to find an original one in good enough shape to
restore. The new boat, which took more than two years to build from
salvaged parts, was commissioned by the U.S. Coast Guard last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''The No. 1 purpose of the museum is to honor the veterans and
the workers of Higgins Industries,'' Ambrose said. ''Everybody
worked one way or another for the war effort. This is symbolic of
all of them, and soon they're not going to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The National D-Day Museum: http://www.ddaymuseum.org
</P>
<P>
   Military community site: http://www.military.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 0200 </TRAILER>
