<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 03:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxury Entices Some Movie-Goers  </HEADLINE>
By HEIDI B. PERLMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) -- Think of it as dinner and a movie --
without the drive in between.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the theaters at Premium Cinemas have
floor-to-ceiling screens, near deafening sound and soft leather
seats, they also feature a gourmet menu featuring everything from
squash ravioli to rib-eye steak.
</P>
<P>
   More than a century after well-dressed theatergoers crowded in
to see the first moving pictures, this new cinema is one of a
handful nationwide trying to turn a night at the movies back into
the event it once was.
</P>
<P>
   From full dinners to Ferris wheel rides to child care, movie
theater owners are doing whatever it takes to lure consumers who
have a range of entertainment options.
</P>
<P>
   ''It used to be that you could pay 25 cents and get more than
just a feature-length movie for your money,'' said Terrance Demas,
director of the League of Historic American Theaters in Baltimore.
''With TV, that somehow got lost. Now, that's what people want
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, theaters took in nearly $7 billion in ticket sales, up
more than $1 billion from the previous year, according to the
National Association of Theater Owners.
</P>
<P>
   But with the rapid growth of new media and home entertainment
systems, theater owners are concerned those numbers could start to
drop if they don't offer more than just popcorn and a movie.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Sony recently opened a 15-screen Metreon
Theater, complete with restaurants, an amusement park, a children's
museum, stores and four IMAX theaters that show multidimensional
films.
</P>
<P>
   Resort Theaters of America is planning to open about 500
theaters at resorts in California, Utah and Colorado which will
offer gourmet coffee, chocolates and pastries in the lobby, a
supervised playroom for children and a digital screen show before
the movie begins.
</P>
<P>
   And in Massachusetts, Wisconsin and Maryland, General Cinemas
has opened Premium Cinemas, where patrons can have dinner --
anything from oven-roasted scrod to chocolate mousse cake -- and see
a movie under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
   At the Framingham location, reservations are recommended and no
one under the age of 21 is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons can dine in a restaurant just outside the cinema. A full
bar is set up for drinks, and slow eaters can take their plates
into the theater. Waiters also offer table service inside the
auditorium for late orders, dessert and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   For the show, moviegoers sit in leather lounge chairs with ample
leg room behind private tables. Popcorn is free -- and waiting at
each reserved seat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sick of being in a crowded theater with kids kicking me
and screaming in my ear,'' said Michael Kelly, 26, of Marlboro,
before a recent showing of ''Mission: Impossible 2.'' ''For me,
just a chance to have a drink and watch a movie without kids around
is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   That much special treatment isn't cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the average price for admission is $4.26, according
to the National Association of Theater Owners. But in major
metropolitan areas, and at most chain theaters, adult ticket prices
range from $5 for matinees to $10 for evening shows.
</P>
<P>
   At the Premium Cinemas, an adult ticket is $15. That doesn't
include appetizers, which start at $7, or entrees, which range from
$12.50 for the squash ravioli to $18.50 for a rib-eye steak.
</P>
<P>
   Two burgers, some chicken satay and two sodas -- refillable -- on
a recent weekday night came to about $32. Add to that a tip for the
service, and two tickets to the movie, and the total cost for the
night comes to just under $70.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's stupid,'' said Julie Feiler, 28, of Cambridge. An avid
movie-goer, she regularly goes to theaters featuring art and
foreign films. And she never buys popcorn or drinks from the snack
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like to sit in the dark and watch a movie,'' she said. ''I
don't need luxuries. If I wanted to be that comfortable, I'd stay
home.''
</P>
<P>
   But some say $15 isn't outrageous, particularly taken in the
context of the cost for other entertainment, such as athletic
events or concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ''People today are just unwilling to go anywhere where they
won't be coddled,'' said Lucy Fischer, head of the Film Studies
Program and the Society for Cinema Studies at the University of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ''And why should they? They've grown up having dinner on couches
in front of big-screen TVs. Why go to the movies at all?''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: League of Historic American Theatres:
http://www.lhat.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.generalcinema.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 0304 </TRAILER>
