<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dame Edna Wins Special Tony  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Actor Barry Humphries, wearing a tuxedo,
accepted a special Tony award for a live theatrical event, ''Dame
Edna: the Royal Tour,'' with the excuse that Dame Edna was
downstairs getting ''prettied up'' to present the Tony for best
costume design.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian, who pretends they're separate people, puts on
flamboyant gowns, wigs and jewelry to portray the warmhearted,
snobbish, funny Dame Edna.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Edna first appeared on stage in 1955, a dowdy, insecure,
shy, Melbourne housewife, mother of three small, unattractive
infants, I little dreamt her career would end on this magnificent
occasion. Not that it's ending,'' he said, accepting his Tony
before the TV cameras began to roll.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this great accolade of my career, my joy is tinged with
disappointment. I had hoped to be nominated for drama. I wrote a
play which is a profound, sensitive meditation on death, love and
the nature of friendship, whereas Edna, with her relentless ad libs
and refusal to learn her lines, has turned it into a frothy
crowd-pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   ''I must thank my producers who, due to the cost of tickets,
unfortunately are not with us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Later when Dame Edna, in full matron-diva regalia, gave the
award for best costume design, she joked: ''I don't have costumes.
I just wear street clothes in my show.''
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna also startled Martin Pakledinaz, who won the costume
Tony for ''Kiss Me, Kate,'' when she kissed him. Pakledinaz, with
Dame Edna's lipstick on his cheek, laughed when he tried, more than
once, to start the acceptance speech he had been told to make
brief.
</P>
<P>
   He finally said, ''I hope this isn't coming out of my 45
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.tonyawards.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 0333 </TRAILER>
