<DOCNO> APW20000605.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 03:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Director Blakemore Blase Over Tonys  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Broadway was buzzing about Michael Blakemore's
head-turning Tony awards coup, but he appeared blase about being
the first director honored for a play and a musical in the same
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have an awful lot of emotions,'' Blakemore insisted
dryly a few minutes after winning best director honors Sunday for
two dramatically different shows -- the cerebral play ''Copenhagen''
and the boisterous Cole Porter musical ''Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards were his first Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters at the awards show pressed for a bigger reaction,
the Australian-born Brit, known for his restraint, reluctantly
conceded he was pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like having twins: You get it all over at once,'' he
said. ''I'm delighted and amazed, really a little stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old's back-to-back wins sent Tony organizers
scurrying for the history books. They quickly confirmed his double
directorial win was a first.
</P>
<P>
   A double victory has been possible only since 1960, when the
direction prize was split into play and musical categories.
Blakemore was nominated for both in 1990 with ''Lettice &AMP; Lovage''
and ''City of Angels,'' but he didn't win for either.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was a big night for both of this year's Blakemore shows.
''Kiss Me, Kate'' won five Tonys, including best musical revival,
and ''Copenhagen,'' a thought-provoking play about a mysterious
World War II meeting between two physicists, took home three,
including best play.
</P>
<P>
   The director is already at work on a new project, the Arthur
Miller play ''Mr. Peters' Connections,'' which will open in London.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I'd known I was going to win two Tonys, I think I would
have retired,'' Blakemore joked.
</P>
<P>
   One reporter asked Blakemore how he planned to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   He was silent for a long moment as he raised a plastic champagne
flute in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something like this, I think,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.tonyawards.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
