<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 08:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HBO Set To Show 'King Gimp'  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It was a startling spectacle on Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   When ''King Gimp'' was named winner for best short documentary,
viewers caught a glimpse of its subject, Dan Keplinger, quaking
with pleasure in his wheelchair in Los Angeles' Shrine Auditorium
audience. Then he flung himself to the floor, a vision of literally
unbridled joy.
</P>
<P>
   Keplinger, who was born with cerebral palsy, had spent much of
his 27 years excluded, ignored and, worst of all, misunderstood.
But on that March night, for a moment, there was no mistaking the
grand things he felt, and everyone who saw him felt the same.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Keplinger is meeting with a reporter at HBO's
Manhattan headquarters. He is up from Baltimore, where he lives, to
publicize the film, airing on HBO Monday from 7 to 7:45 p.m.
Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   ''King Gimp,'' which Keplinger wrote, tells his story from
childhood through his mid-20s. Along with more mundane triumphs
such as microwaving popcorn and serving himself, the film records
his rebirth as an artist while in high school. It captures him
graduating from Towson University with a major in art. It shows him
at work, painting with a brush he mounts on a helmet-like device.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I paint, there is a sweet siren voice telling me where
the brush will move,'' he writes, pecking out each letter on a
keyboard with his headstick. ''I obey the brush.''
</P>
<P>
   It is his art, as well as the film, that has brought Dan
Keplinger to Manhattan. During June, two dozen of his expressionist
oils -- bold and unyielding, many of them self-portraits -- are for
sale at Soho's Phyllis Kind Gallery. (And displayed on HBO's Web
site.) It's his first major solo show.
</P>
<P>
   And the latest confirmation of his feisty nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people think 'gimp' means someone with a lame walk,''
Keplinger declares at the start of the film. ''But 'gimp' also
means 'fighting spirit.'''
</P>
<P>
   It does. Look it up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our film isn't about a disability, it's about a spirit,''
William Whiteford is telling the reporter. ''It's about a person.
With an attitude.'' And he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteford and Susan Hannah Hadary are the Baltimore-based,
Oscar-winning producers of ''King Gimp.'' Part of Keplinger's life
since he was 12, they have joined him, with his mother, Linda
Ritter, for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''The beauty of what we do as filmmakers is developing
relationships,'' Whiteford goes on. They filmed Keplinger for 13
years. Not that they expected it would go on so long. ''Each time
we would think of ending it, Dan's life would take a new turn.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Finally, with his college graduation, we said, 'That's it!'''
adds Hadary.
</P>
<P>
   Keplinger chortles. ''At one point, they were going to lock me
up so I couldn't do any more.''
</P>
<P>
   He even helped them finish ''King Gimp'' by screening footage as
a summer job, then writing the narration himself. It tells of
living in a world that often had no place for him, where ''no one
could understand that I was this intelligent person inside of this
body.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are taking more time to listen to me now,'' he says
when asked about the film's impact. ''They know I have something to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that everyone can make out what he says when he speaks. His
lack of muscular control affects his voice as much as anything
else. His speech erupts -- at least, to the unpracticed ear -- in
mostly unintelligible grunts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dan and I always talked a lot,'' his mother says. And with
obvious affection and not too much trouble, she and his filmmaker
friends share interpreting duties during this interview, as
Keplinger hacks away at too-common misconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   No, he explains, he isn't in any discomfort. What looks like
writhing and grimacing is involuntary movement that he chooses not
to tame with drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''My arms spring out and people think I'm getting excited and
tell me to calm down,'' he says, setting up his punch line: ''I am
only trying to get back together!''
</P>
<P>
   No, he doesn't feel plagued by limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ''What people think is hard for me I think is normal,'' he
insists. ''People think I'm having a terrible time doing something.
I just think I'm doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keplinger moves through life with one towering advantage: He
never counts on the easy way.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, his mother taught him never to think too far
ahead about hardships that may never come to pass. As a young
single mother determined to raise him like a normal child, she had
to stay in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I was worrying when he was 9 about how, when he's 25, he's
going to be heavy and how am I gonna lift him, it would have taken
away the energy I needed to get him past 9. You know? I tell Dan,
you eat an elephant a bite at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   As viewers will discover, ''King Gimp'' documents a splendid
first course.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   ''Virtual exhibit'' of Dan Keplinger's art: http://www.hbo.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
