<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Settle Phone Cost Dispute  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to referee a
dispute over federal rules intended to keep telephone service
affordable in high-cost areas.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will hear an appeal by the local phone company
GTE.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the justices rejected an appeal by AT&AMP;T and
MCI involving subsidies for Internet hookups for schools and
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission long has had rules
designed to ensure affordable ''universal service'' for everyone,
including people in rural and other high-cost areas. Before 1996,
the rules involved shifting costs to other customers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress passed the Telecommunications Act, designed to
open local phone markets to full competition. Because competition
could erode the universal-service subsidies, Congress directed the
FCC to write new rules.
</P>
<P>
   The law also introduced new subsidies for Internet access in
schools and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The commission adopted rules requiring all telecommunications
companies to contribute to the universal-service subsidies, based
on their revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The commission decided that phone carriers' contributions to
high-cost customers should be based only on the carriers'
interstate revenue. But their contributions to the Internet hookup
program were to be based on both interstate and in-state revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Subsidies given to companies serving high-cost customers would
be based mainly on the future cost of providing such service, the
commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Various telecommunications companies challenged the rules,
including AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals largely upheld the rules
last July. It generally upheld the rules for subsidies to high-cost
areas, but it said contributions for Internet hookups could be
based only on companies' interstate revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal granted today, GTE argued that the subsidies it
receives for serving high-cost customers are unfairly calculated in
a way that understates the real cost.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and MCI said companies' subsidy contributions for the
Internet program should be based on their in-state revenue as well
as interstate revenue. Otherwise, they said, long-distance
companies such as AT&AMP;T and MCI would pay a much larger share of the
subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers urged the justices to deny both
appeals even though they said the appeals court erred in saying
companies' subsidy payments for the Internet program could be based
only on their interstate revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers said that issue was a narrow one and
did not warrant Supreme Court review.
</P>
<P>
   The cases are GTE Service Corp. vs. FCC, 99-1244, and AT&AMP;T vs.
Cincinnati Bell Telephone Co., 99-1249.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Texas Office of
Public Utility Counsel vs. FCC: http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html
and click on 5th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
