<HEADLINE> Dow Down 23; Nasdaq Down 12  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened modestly lower today as investors
took some profits from last week's sharp gains.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 23.33 at 10,771.43.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Nasdaq composite
index was down 11.79 at 3,801.59, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 7.53 at 1,469.73.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said a mild decline was to be expected today as
investors capture some gains from a strong, broad-based rally last
week. The Nasdaq rose 19 percent last week, the index's strongest
performance in history and a dramatic departure from the weakness
it demonstrated in March and April.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the technology stocks that dominate the Nasdaq turned in
a mixed performance.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm fell $4.063 to $68.625. Over the weekend, China United
Telecommunications confirmed that it won't use a mobile-phone
technology designed by Qualcomm for at least three years.
Speculation about the China contract had heightened volatility in
Qualcomm shares in the past few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba rose $7.75 to $78.25 after the company formed a
partnership with VeriSign Inc. and American Express to provide a
card payment processing function for online business-to-business
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were anticipating a fairly quiet week. Last week's
rally was driven by a stream of economic data that showed a modest
slowdown in the economy. That encouraged investors to believe that
the Federal Reserve may not need to aggressively raise interest
rates to keep inflation from rearing up.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the only economic report expected to move markets is
the Labor Department's Producer Price Index, due out on Friday.
With a dearth of news, the market may struggle to find direction,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 110.33 million
shares, well behind Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies slipped 0.24 to
512.79.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.4 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.7 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
