<DOCNO> APW20000605.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Director Blakemore Wins Two Tonys  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Tony awards kissed ''Kate,'' ''Copenhagen''
and ''Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadway's top honor also kissed Michael Blakemore twice, as the
71-year-old director won awards for his direction of both a
musical, ''Kiss Me, Kate,'' and a play, ''Copenhagen,'' a Tony
first.
</P>
<P>
   The 1948 Cole Porter musical was the night's big winner, picking
up five awards, including the prize for musical revival. Michael
Frayn's dense drama of physics and friendship was named best play.
''Contact,'' an innovative dance musical devised by Susan Stroman
and John Weidman, was chosen best musical.
</P>
<P>
   But Blakemore was the man of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I can say is 'Thank you, America.' And by America, I mean
New York. And by New York, I mean Broadway,'' the director said
during his second trip to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Besides director and musical-revival, ''Kate'' won prizes for
its leading man, Brian Stokes Mitchell, as well as for costumes and
orchestrations.
</P>
<P>
   Stroman's work on ''Contact'' won her the prize for best
choreography, while two of the show's featured (supporting)
performers, Boyd Gaines and Karen Ziemba, also were honored. It was
Gaines' third Tony, having won previously for ''The Heidi
Chronicles'' and a revival of ''She Loves Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Dance has lifts and dips and unexpected turns just as real
life does. Had I not fallen in love with Mike Ockrent, I could have
never have written 'Contact,''' said an emotional Stroman
referring, to her husband, a director who died in December of
leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Tony nominators ignored ''Aida'' in the best-musical category,
but the Disney musical had its own revenge, doing surprising well
in the numbers race. It tied ''Contact'' with four Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Headley, its radiant star, was named best actress in a
musical as the crowd at Radio City Music Hall cheered its approval.
An emotional Headley told Disney: ''I will work for you for the
rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Elton John and Tim Rice picked up an award for their
pop-flavored score and the lavish musical, set in ancient Egypt,
also got Tonys for scenic and lighting design.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Real Thing,'' Tom Stoppard's meditation on the love,
captured the prize for revival-play as well as the top acting
awards for its two stars -- Stephen Dillane and Jennifer Ehle. The
actress was up against her mother, Rosemary Harris, in the
actress-play category.
</P>
<P>
   Several productions went home empty handed including ''Dirty
Blonde,'' Claudia Shear's play about Mae West; a Stroman-directed
revival of Meredith Willson's ''The Music Man'' and George Wolfe's
adaptation of ''The Wild Party,'' which has been struggling at the
box office.
</P>
<P>
   ''A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' the critically praised revival
of Eugene O'Neill's play, could manage only one award -- to veteran
British performer Roy Dotrice for his portrayal of a whiskey-soaked
Connecticut farmer in the featured category. The featured actress
prize went to Blair Brown of ''Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Dead,'' a musical adaptation of the James Joyce short
story, also managed only one award: book of a musical for Richard
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Australian actor Barry Humphries -- better known as Dame Edna --
provided the evening's comic highlight. Dame Edna presented the
award for costume design as well as a big, messy kiss to Martin
Pakledinaz of ''Kiss Me, Kate.'' A lipstick-smeared Pakledinaz was
so flustered that he had a hard time delivering his acceptance
speech.
</P>
<P>
   After a year off, Rosie O'Donnell returning as a host of the CBS
Tony telecast didn't improve its typically anemic ratings. In
Nielsen overnights -- reflecting about one-half of the nation's TV
homes -- it notched a 7.2 rating and 11 share of audience, down from
a 7.8 rating and 13 share in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Donnell worked smoothly with co-host Nathan Lane in
moving the show along -- so smoothly that it came up a minute or two
short. The two comics had to vamp until the credits started
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The winners in 21 categories were chosen by 705 members of the
theatrical profession and journalists. The Tony awards were started
in 1947 by the American Theater Wing, a theater service
organization. They were named after the late Antoinette Perry, an
actress and past chairwoman of the theater wing.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.tonyawards.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
