<HEADLINE> Dow Up 20; Nasdaq Up 8  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were moving between modest gains and
losses today as investors took some profits from last week's sharp
gains but continued rewarding technology companies with strong
growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 19.50 at 10,814.26.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 7.96 at 3,821.34, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 6.92 at 1,470.34.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was very quiet as investors captured some gains from a
strong, broad-based rally last week. The Nasdaq rose 19 percent
last week, the index's biggest weekly gain in history and a
dramatic departure from the weakness it demonstrated in March and
April.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the technology stocks that dominate the Nasdaq turned in
a mixed performance.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm fell $4.50 to $68.188. Over the weekend, China United
Telecommunications confirmed it won't use a mobile phone technology
designed by Qualcomm for at least three years. Speculation about
the China contract had heightened volatility in Qualcomm shares in
the past few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com fell $4.688 to $53.188, following a 15 percent gain
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba rose $8.063 to $78.563 after the company formed a
partnership with VeriSign Inc. and American Express to provide a
card payment processing function for online business-to-business
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Advanced Micro Devices rose
$3.25 to $92.125. The company has introduced a souped-up version of
its Athlon computer chip and a new bargain brand; both products are
viewed as a challenge to industry leader Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Merger activity stimulated some trading. Primark rose $8.313 to
$37.313 after Thomson Corp. agreed to buy it for $842 million in
cash. Both companies are providers of professional and financial
information.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors were still reveling in last week's good
economic news. A stream of economic data showed a modest slowdown
in the economy, which many investors interpreted as a sign that the
Federal Reserve may not need to aggressively raise interest rates
to keep inflation from rearing up.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is now a widespread perception that the Fed won't raise
rates at its June meeting, and perhaps that they're done for the
year,'' said Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank
Securities. ''It will be hard for them to justify raising interest
rates when there is evidence of a slowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the only economic report expected to move markets is
the Labor Department's Producer Price Index, due out on Friday.
With a dearth of news, the market may struggle to find direction,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dallas Federal Reserve President Robert McTeer said
today that there's little question that the Fed's six interest-rate
increases in the past year are having the desired effect. But he
cautioned against placing too much stock in one month's figures.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, he said, ''are always all over the place and it
remains to be seen whether this is a fluke or signs of a changing
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 654.55 million
shares, well behind Friday's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies slipped 0.50 to
512.53.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
