<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen Byrd Nears Firearms Center Deal  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Robert Byrd, one of the Senate's masters
of winning federal dollars for the folks back home, is close to an
agreement that would put a $24.9 million government firearms
training center in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging deal would set aside roughly 30 acres of federal
land just outside historic Harpers Ferry, W.Va., a compromise from
an original plan that angered preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's initial proposal for the facility, where the Treasury
Department is to train hundreds of federal agents annually,
involved 327 acres. That was supported by local business owners,
but preservationists complained about potential development and
said the plan would mar the scene of one of Confederate Gen. Thomas
''Stonewall'' Jackson's most impressive victories.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists said Monday that the tentative deal was a
positive development, but said they still wanted to see details.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a 41-year Senate veteran, had inserted language into an
agriculture spending bill providing the money to build the center
and transferring the 327 acres to the Treasury Department from the
Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   But under the tentative compromise, the Treasury Department
would receive only about 30 acres. The remainder would be used
''for preservation'' and remain controlled by the Fish and Wildlife
Service, along with the National Park Service, according to a
written statement by Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Byrd all along has been interested in preserving the historic
portions of the property,'' the senator's spokeswoman, Ann Adler,
said Monday in describing the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Guide, deputy assistant secretary for policy for the
Interior Department, said there was ''a conceptual agreement,''
adding, ''There is no reason why we can't work out'' a final
agreement to change Byrd's original language.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department is parent agency of the Fish and
Wildlife Service and the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rosa, executive director of the Harpers Ferry Conservancy,
a nonprofit land preservation group, called the new plan ''a major
step in the right direction.'' But he said he wanted to see
specific details about plans for the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Argust, lobbyist with the National Parks Conservation
Association in Washington, said she was concerned that Byrd's
language would still sidestep federal requirements for an
environmental review and consideration of an alternative site.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not quite there yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, 82, has brought well over $1 billion in federal projects
to his home state of West Virginia since becoming chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Committee in 1989. Since 1995, with
Republicans in the majority, he has been top Democrat on that
committee, which oversees one-third of the $1.8 trillion federal
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Harpers Ferry, about 65 miles from Washington, was the site of
abolitionist John Brown's ill-fated raid on a federal arsenal there
in 1859. In 1862, Jackson outmaneuvered a federal garrison in the
bombed-out city and captured more than 12,500 U.S. troops, the most
Northern soldiers to surrender in any Civil War engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists have long wanted to add more than 1,000 acres --
including the entire Fish and Wildlife Service tract -- to the
existing 2,345-acre Harpers Ferry National Historical Park.
</P>
<P>
   Local builders and business people have supported the training
center and, in some cases, using some of the Fish and Wildlife land
for development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1542 </TRAILER>
