<HEADLINE> Clinton Draws Jeers From Heckler  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- For Vladimir Zhirinovsky, President Clinton's
address to the Russian Duma was hardly an occasion to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shame!'' the ultranationalist leader shouted at his colleagues
as Clinton left the podium.''Whom are you applauding?''
</P>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky talked loudly throughout Clinton's 50-minute speech
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him in English, lift the blockade on Iraq, withdraw
troops from Yugoslavia and do not intervene in Russian affairs,''
Zhirinovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the first American president to address the Russian
parliament, ignored the flamboyant lawmaker, whose previous antics
included throwing water on deputies and a fight in which he pulled
a female colleague's hair.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Zhirinovsky complained that the U.S. Secret Service
took over the legislative building -- ''They behave like
occupiers!'' he cried -- and claimed that the Russian government had
to bring in people to pad the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were practically no deputies in the hall -- only hired
people brought in from the Foreign Ministry and the Federal
Security Service,'' Zhirinovsky told reporters.''They also brought
cleaning women and other technical personnel here -- and Clinton
thought he was speaking to members of the Russian parliament!''
</P>
<P>
   There were several dozen empty seats in the hall, and
Zhirinovsky said only 120 of the 450 deputies were present.
</P>
<P>
   But Boris Gryzlov, head of the pro-Kremlin Unity group, said
about 300 deputies had attended the session. And legislator Andrei
Kokoshin said some deputies were erroneously told that the speech
would start an hour after it actually did.
</P>
</TEXT>
