<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechens Appeal to Americans  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chechen leaders are appealing to Americans to
help accomplish what official Washington and the international
community couldn't -- stop the war in their devastated republic.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by several former cabinet members, actor Richard Gere and
other prominent Americans, Ilyas Akhmadov, who acts as Chechnya's
foreign minister Monday announced a proposal for a cease-fire and
investigation of alleged war crimes in the independence-minded
Russian region.
</P>
<P>
   ''The war has been going on for nine months already and it
brings a lot of suffering to ... civilians,'' Akhmadov said,
estimating the dead at 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Akhmadov, not officially recognized by the U.S. government
because Chechnya is not a recognized nation, said the peace
proposal was sent to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. He said
he will promote it in meetings with senators, congressmen and
Clinton administration officials during a two-week visit.
</P>
<P>
   Akhmadov was encouraged to visit the United States by the
American Committee for Chechnya, a Washington-based group formed a
few months ago, said member Irena Lasota. He said he came to call
Americans' attention to the peace proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Other members include former national security advisers Zbigniew
Brzezinski and Robert McFarlane, former Defense Secretary Casper
Weinberger and former Secretary of State Alexander Haig, as well as
other former U.S. diplomats, according to its Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Akhmadov said he wasn't asking the United States to mediate, but
that it ''influence, somehow, the Russian side.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal seeks a cease-fire and creation of a monitoring
committee to include the warring sides as well as the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe and the human rights
watchdog Council of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Shurgalin, spokesman for the Russian Embassy, said
officials there hadn't seen the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov has called for talks with
Moscow before. Moscow has indicated it is looking for a political
solution, but has said repeatedly it will not negotiate with rebels
unless they give up their weapons and turn over any hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians also question whether Maskhadov has authority over
the fractured rebel command to enforce a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials, and other nations, have
repeatedly told Moscow they oppose the Russian crackdown in
Chechnya, particularly the humanitarian crisis. President Clinton
repeated that again to President Vladimir Putin in his weekend
summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
