<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 21 in Quiet Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 )	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended an extremely quiet session with
mixed results as investors took some profits from last week's sharp
gains but continued rewarding technology companies with strong
growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 20.54 at 10,815.30.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was very calm as investors captured some gains from a
strong, broad-based rally last week. The Nasdaq rose 19 percent
last week, the index's biggest weekly gain in history and a
dramatic departure from the weakness it demonstrated in March and
April.
</P>
<P>
   The essential optimism that drove the market's rally last week
remained intact, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market's doing extremely well,'' said Edward Yardeni,
chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities. ''The summer rally
clearly is upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yardeni cautioned that the market may still struggle for
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may cover a lot of territory in a short period of time and
go sideways for a while,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the technology stocks that dominate the Nasdaq turned in
a mixed performance.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm fell. Over the weekend, China United Telecommunications
confirmed it won't use a mobile phone technology designed by
Qualcomm for at least three years. Speculation about the China
contract had heightened volatility in Qualcomm shares in the past
few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com fell, following a 15 percent gain on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba rose after the company formed a partnership with VeriSign
Inc. and American Express to provide a card payment processing
function for online business-to-business transactions.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Advanced Micro Devices rose. The
company has introduced a souped-up version of its Athlon computer
chip and a new bargain brand; both products are viewed as a
challenge to industry leader Intel.
</P>
<P>
   IBM rose sharply, keeping the Dow in positive territory. Merrill
Lynch analyst Steven Milunovich said that while the company's
second-quarter earnings may be fairly mediocre, profit growth is
accelerating and should provide for a strong second half.
</P>
<P>
   Merger activity stimulated some trading. Primark rose after
Thomson Corp. agreed to buy it for $842 million in cash. Both
companies are providers of professional and financial information.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors were still reveling in last week's good
economic news. A stream of economic data showed a modest slowdown
in the economy, which many investors interpreted as a sign that the
Federal Reserve may not need to aggressively raise interest rates
to prevent a flareup of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is now a widespread perception that the Fed won't raise
rates at its June meeting, and perhaps that they're done for the
year,'' Yardeni said. ''It will be hard for them to justify raising
interest rates when there is evidence of a slowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the only economic report expected to move markets is
the Labor Department's Producer Price Index, due out on Friday.
With a dearth of news, the market may struggle to find direction,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dallas Federal Reserve President Robert McTeer said
today there's little question that the Fed's six interest-rate
increases in the past year are having the desired effect. But he
cautioned against placing too much stock in one month's figures.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, he said, ''are always all over the place and it
remains to be seen whether this is a fluke or signs of a changing
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
