<DOCNO> APW20000605.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Dismisses Hubbell Charge  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court wiped out presidential
friend Webster Hubbell's guilty plea to a misdemeanor tax charge
Monday, saying he could not be prosecuted with documents he was
forced to provide under immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is abundantly clear that ... (Hubbell's) act of producing
subpoenaed documents was the first step in a chain of evidence that
led to this prosecution,'' Justice John Paul Stevens wrote in the
court's 8-1 decision that bolstered the Constitution's Fifth
Amendment privilege against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ''The documents did not magically appear in the prosecutor's
office like 'manna from heaven,''' Stevens said. ''They arrived
there only after (Hubbell) asserted his constitutional privilege,
received a grant of immunity'' and provided the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, in a telephone interview, said, ''It's a nice victory
but it's even a better victory for the Constitution ... We've
always felt we were right on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, John W. Nields Jr., said that if the court had ruled
the other way, ''prosecutors all over the country could begin their
investigations by serving broad document subpoenas on their
subjects and just looking through the documents to see what they
can find.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell pleaded guilty to the tax charge last year on condition
his plea would be dismissed if the Supreme Court ruled in his favor
on whether the documents could be used. In doing so Monday, the
nation's highest court ordered the charge against him dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell had reached the plea agreement with former independent
counsel Kenneth Starr, who was replaced by Robert W. Ray last
October. Ray's office said it would seek dismissal of Hubbell's
plea and said that following the ruling, ''federal prosecutors
should now be able to accurately predict the full consequences'' of
granting such immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Fifth Amendment has trumped the Office of Independent
Counsel,'' said William Moffitt, president of the National
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell was the former No. 3 official at the Justice Department
early in President Clinton's first term and has been a friend of
the president and his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton since their
Arkansas days.
</P>
<P>
   The misdemeanor tax charge alleged that Hubbell evaded paying
taxes on income he received from friends of the Clintons during a
1994 investigation of Hubbell by Starr, who was appointed to probe
the Clintons' Whitewater real estate dealings.
</P>
<P>
   The tax charge, filed in April 1998, was based partly on
Hubbell's financial papers, which he was required to give
prosecutors under a limited grant of immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Fifth Amendment protects criminal defendants from
being forced to testify against themselves, it does not protect the
contents of private documents someone created voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   However, the amendment can protect people from being forced to
give such documents to prosecutors when that involves confirming
their existence and authenticity -- a form of testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell argued that prosecutors could not use his papers to
prosecute him after giving him immunity to turn them over. A
federal judge agreed and dismissed the charge.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
revived the charge in January 1999 but said prosecutors could use
information from the documents only by showing they had
''reasonably particular knowledge'' of their existence.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office conceded it could not meet that standard and
agreed to dismiss Hubbell's plea if the Supreme Court upheld the
appeals court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' opinion noted that people can be required to provide
incriminating evidence, such as blood or handwriting samples. But
in being forced to turn over documents, Hubbell had to ''make
extensive use of the contents of his own mind,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here the government has not shown that it had any prior
knowledge of either the existence or the whereabouts of the 13,120
pages of documents ultimately produced'' by Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' opinion was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter, Clarence
Thomas, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer. Thomas wrote
separately for himself and Scalia that the Fifth Amendment's
protection against self-incrimination may be even broader than
Monday's ruling indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist dissented, saying he agreed
with a judge who dissented from the federal appeals court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Not affected by Monday's case is Hubbell's guilty plea to a
felony charge involving legal work for a savings and loan at the
center of the Whitewater investigation. He was sentenced to a year
of probation on that charge in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The case is U.S. vs. Hubbell, 99-166.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For current Supreme Court decisions:
http://www.supremecourtus.gov or http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
