<HEADLINE> OAS May Recognize Fujimori Victory  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- Avoiding a harsh response to Peru's
controversial presidential election, the Organization of American
States considered recognizing Alberto Fujimori's victory while
urging an investigation into vote irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution proposed by host Canada, still undergoing
back-room negotiations over wording before reaching the full OAS
general assembly, would stop short of any sanctions against Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for Peru's May 28 run-off vote was plagued with
irregularities, prompting an OAS observer mission to pull out and
Fujimori's opponent to boycott the vote. The United States and
other nations denounced Fujimori's re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   At Peru's insistence, OAS foreign ministers here dropped
language in the resolution that questioned the election results,
Peruvian Foreign Minister Fernando de Trazegnies said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The current proposal notes that problems tainted the democratic
electoral process, and calls for an investigative mission to head
to Peru ''immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   That mission, comprising OAS Secretary General Cesar Gaviria of
Colombia and Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy,
would work with the government and other political groups on
reforming the election process and bolstering freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   The Peru election was the main issue of the second day of the
OAS three-day general assembly, following protests Sunday by
free-trade activists that led to 41 arrests and prompted
overwhelming security measures.
</P>
<P>
   No protesters turned up at the downtown Windsor meeting site by
mid-afternoon Monday, probably due as much to cold, rainy weather
that descended on this southern Ontario city across the border from
Detroit as to the armed riot police patrolling downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   Outside an OAS luncheon elsewhere, scores of demonstrators
linked arms and sat down in the rain to block delegates from
entering. Police had to pick up some of the protesters to clear the
road. No arrests were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The protests Sunday were the largest in memory at an OAS
gathering and brought the grouping of 34 countries face-to-face
with the anti-free trade movement that disrupted a World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle in December and also evoked street
clashes at an International Monetary Fund meeting in Washington
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Stein, the Guatemalan diplomat who headed the OAS
election mission in Peru, said Monday his group pointed out voting
irregularities, such as illegal use of public resources by Fujimori
and moves to stifle the opposition and judiciary. The mission left
Peru before the run-off vote when its request to examine new
computer software introduced to count the ballots was denied.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori won 51.2 percent of the vote in a run-off after
challenger Alejandro Toledo boycotted the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mission tried to pinpoint some key issues that, if
addressed properly, would have given back a substantial amount of
trust that was lost,'' Stein said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   A human rights report has accused the South American country of
failing to meet democratic election standards. Former President
Jimmy Carter joined two former Latin American leaders in an open
letter to the OAS meeting that also criticized the Peru election.
</P>
<P>
   Some OAS nations including the United States wanted a harsh
response to Peru, possibly sanctions, which must be recommended by
the foreign ministers. Other nations, including Brazil and Mexico,
argued the OAS should stay out of internal electoral issues.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Organization of American States, http://www.oas.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
