<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tony Ratings Down From Last Year  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rosie's return did not help the Tony Awards in
the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Rosie O'Donnell's reappearance as host, the two-hour
broadcast on CBS Sunday night dropped to a 7.2 rating and 11 share
of the audience, down from a 7.8 rating and a 13 share last year,
according to preliminary Nielsen figures released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all a little disappointed,'' said Tony spokesman Keith
Sherman. ''But the competition was stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was up against several potent opponents, including
ABC's powerhouse ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' the Los Angeles
Lakers-Portland Trail Blazers NBA playoff game on NBC and the
season premiere of ''Sex and the City'' on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell had served as host of the show in 1997 and 1998,
dropping out last year because of a busy schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The television program was a boost, however, for Sunday night's
big Tony winners -- ''Copenhagen,'' ''Contact'' and ''Kiss Me,
Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   The three, which won awards for best play, musical and
musical-revival respectively, reported sizable jumps Monday in
box-office receipts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Contact,'' the innovative dance musical about relationships
between men and women, was expected to double its daily box-office
take to around $400,000, according to producer Bernard Gersten. The
show, at Lincoln Center's Vivian Beaumont Theater, is selling
tickets through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The future looks bleak, though, for at least one musical shut
out of the prizes Sunday night. ''The Wild Party'' was nominated
for seven awards and didn't win any. Its producers are expected to
decide by Tuesday whether to keep the show -- which opened in April
to mixed reviews -- running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
