<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lanka Lifts Foreign Media Censor  </HEADLINE>
By DILIP GANGULY
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Sri Lanka's military said Monday it
killed 1,000 rebels during May in fighting for the northern Jaffna
peninsula, and the government stiffened its stand on pursuing peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the government lifted censorship on foreign news
media coverage of the 17-year civil war. It continued censorship on
the local news media.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing the separatists of duplicity, President Chandrika
Kumaratunga said there was no point in holding talks with them.
</P>
<P>
   ''For six years we have tried to talk to them and for six years
they have lied,'' Kumaratunga told the British Broadcasting Corp.
in an interview broadcast Monday. ''They have deceived foreign
countries and governments on the pretext they are going to talk and
up to date they have refused to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry's top spokesman, Brig. Palitha Fernando,
said 1,000 Tamil Tiger rebels have been killed and an equal number
wounded in fighting in the past month in the Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have come to this figure after monitoring terrorists'
transmissions and from information from our units,'' Fernando told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   He said 800 of the deaths were in the first three weeks of May,
while a lull in the fighting since then has resulted in only 200
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent confirmation of his statement. The
government does not allow journalists to the war zone. However,
fighting has decreased in the region, which suggests the rebels may
have suffered losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamil Tigers did not comment on their Web sites. The group,
which is banned in Sri Lanka, also does not allow journalists into
combat areas.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga decided to end a month of censorship on what
foreign-based news media send to the rest of the world because
''they have been very responsible,'' Media Minister Mangala
Samaraweera said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sri Lankan government said foreign reports about the
civil war will continue to be censored before they can be printed
or broadcast locally.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam have been fighting since
1983 to create a homeland for Sri Lanka's Tamil minority, who make
up 18 percent of the 18.6 million population. The war has left
62,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rebels made spectacular military gains in the past
two months, since May 22 their advances were halted by troops with
better weapons bought from international markets.
</P>
<P>
   In a sea battle Monday, Tamil Tiger rebels destroyed an
Israeli-made navy attack craft while the Sri Lankan air force sank
another by mistake, a Sri Lankan naval officer told The Associated
Press on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The naval officer said the air force mistakenly fired on one of
the navy's Dvoras, which then sank. The officer said he could not
confirm how many men were on the boat or what happened to them, but
he said such craft normally carry about 15 crew.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice of Tigers rebel radio, monitored in the town of
Vavuniya, said the insurgents killed 15 government sailors and lost
13 fighters in the sea battle.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, foot patrols shot and killed seven rebels in the
outskirts of Jaffna city, said government spokesman and chief
censor Ariya Rubasinghe. There was no mention of government
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 40,000 soldiers are defending Jaffna from attacks
by rebels seeking to regain their stronghold of 1990-95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
