<HEADLINE> Wagner Family Clashes Over Festival  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The family feud between Richard Wagner's
descendants over the world-famous music festival he inaugurated was
dragging out to Wagnerian-like lengths, after the festival board
put off a decision Monday on who would head the event.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over who should direct the festival has been brewing
for years, but it won't be resolved until after this summer's
festival in the Bavarian city of Bayreuth.
</P>
<P>
   ''High Noon in Bayreuth'' was how Berlin's Tagesspiegel
newspaper labeled the showdown between Wagner's 80-year-old
grandson, who has led the festival for nearly 50 years, and other
descendants, who want to breathe fresh life into the staid corners
of German culture.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever gains the directorship could make major changes to the
festival Wagner started by staging the premiere of his 18-hour Ring
opera series in 1876.
</P>
<P>
   However, the board postponed its decision because two candidates
-- Wagner's great-grandchildren Eva Wagner-Pasquier and Wieland
Lafferentz -- decided to vie for the directorship separately, rather
than together, and needed time to form individual proposals for the
festival, said Josef Erhard of the Bavaria state Culture Ministry,
chairman of the festival foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have until Oct. 1 to come up with their plans,
Erhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Current director Wolfgang Wagner has insisted he will stay on in
the job under his lifetime contract, unless the board chooses his
wife and longtime assistant, Gudrun, to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   But the voices for change are numerous and have the support of
lawmakers looking to cut the festival's subsidies. Along with four
members of the Wagner family, the 24-member festival board includes
members of federal, state and local government.
</P>
<P>
   Other Wagner descendants have called for major changes to the
festival. Great-granddaughter Nike Wagner proposed replacing some
traditional pieces with other Wagner works typically unheard at the
festival, as well as with works by other composers.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested inviting corporate sponsorship and holding added
festival events on Bayreuth's main square outside the Festspielhaus
theater, which Wagner designed as the ideal stage for his work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
