<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks Ukrainians  </HEADLINE>
By MARINA SYSOYEVA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- To the suprise and delight of many
Ukrainians, President Clinton addressed them repeatedly Monday in
their own language, borrowing the words of beloved national poet
Taras Shevchenko.
</P>
<P>
   ''Borites, poboryte!'' Clinton exhorted. The phrase, which means
''fight and you shall overcome,'' drew cheers from thousands of
people who packed into a downtown plaza to hear Clinton speak.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe Ukraine has the best opportunity in a thousand years
to achieve both freedom and prosperity,'' Clinton said. ''Do not
give up. Keep on fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the phrase at least four times during his speech,
which he ended with another native phrase: ''Slava Ukraina'' --
''Glory to Ukraine.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He chose the key words to say,'' a woman told Ukraine's One
Plus One TV. ''He told us to fight ... and I heard that there is
freedom waiting ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Police and television reports estimated more than 50,000 people
came to the central Mykhailivska Square to listen to Clinton,
undeterred by 86-degree temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight, however, and many frustrated Ukrainians
remained outside police cordons even though they were wearing
invitations they had received in the mail days earlier. An
enterprising company handed out leaflets advertising the new
''President'' brand of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Ukrainian television reported that there were some 2,500
plainclothes officers and security agents on the square, while
sharpshooters were posted on surrounding roofs and church bell
towers.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience hoped to hear that Washington was ready to
provide aid for closing down the Chernobyl nuclear power plant --
which Clinton had already announced during his meeting with
President Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived at the square after his session with Kuchma and
went into the newly reconstructed, gold-domed Mikhailivsky
Cathedral, which was demolished during the rule of Soviet dictator
Joseph Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging soon afterward, he laid a wreath at a small monument to
millions of Ukrainians who died during Stalin's forced famine of
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   While mournful music played, Clinton stood on a blue and yellow
podium -- Ukraine's national colors -- flanked by two girls who had
participated in a U.S. exchange program. Both greeted Clinton with
short speeches in Ukrainian and English.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd waved small U.S. and Ukrainian flags and cheered as
Clinton urged them not to despair on the difficult road to
democracy and economic rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing his speech to the peals of church bells, Clinton went
straight to the crowd, shaking outstretched hands and reaching
beyond the first rows of people to those who tried to grab his hand
from farther back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1722 </TRAILER>
