<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernobyl Closure Problems Abound  </HEADLINE>
By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Ukrainian leader Leonid Kuchma's plan to
close the troubled Chernobyl power plant will take years to
complete because of an array of technical and social complications.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the logistics of dismantling a facility filled with
radioactive material and aging machinery, Ukraine faces the
question of what will happen to thousands of people who depend on
the plant for their livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''To our sorrow, political decisions precede the technical
ones,'' Chernobyl spokesman Oleh Holosokov told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Once Chernobyl's sole remaining reactor No. 3 is taken out of
service, maintaining the plant will cost about $6 million a year
until its nuclear fuel is completely unloaded -- a process that is
expected to take about five years.
</P>
<P>
   The first and second of Chernobyl's four reactors, already
idled, required twice that amount for maintenance this year, but
the government was too strapped to finance it completely, Holosokov
said. The other reactor was destroyed in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the closure, many of the reactor systems would have
to be dismantled, and those contaminated by radioactivity would
have to undergo deactivation. The plan also requires construction
of new facilities such as a $30 million heating plant and
reprocessing and storage sites for liquid nuclear waste and spent
fuel rods.
</P>
<P>
   The planned closure also poses a social problem: unemployment.
Chernobyl employed nearly 5,900 workers, so about 4,000 workers in
nearby towns will be left jobless. Immediate layoffs may affect up
to 3,000 workers, Chernobyl officials say.
</P>
<P>
   A 1999 law makes former Chernobyl employees eligible for
financial assistance from the state for more than a year while they
seek work elsewhere, but it remains unclear whether Ukraine's
struggling government will find enough money to help them.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine's economy has been declining since the Soviet Union
collapsed in 1991, and the country has few resources to deal with
the consequences of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Kiev estimate the Chernobyl accident affected 3.4
million of Ukraine's 50 million people. At least 4,365 of those who
took part in the hasty cleanup effort have died, government figures
indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 400,000 adults and 1.1 million children are entitled
to state aid for Chernobyl-related health problems. Yet government
funding covered little more than 50 percent of Chernobyl relief
needs between 1996 and 1998, and only about one-third last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine has pinned its hopes on international aid, particularly
on a donor nations' conference scheduled for July. ''We hope the
Chernobyl announcement will give a new impulse and cause
enthusiasm'' among donors, said Deputy Foreign Minister Oleksandr
Chalyi.
</P>
<P>
   The donors are expected to focus on the so-called
''sarcophagus,'' a leaky steel and concrete structure covering the
reactor that exploded and which is believed to contain tons of
nuclear fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of making Chernobyl environmentally safe has been
estimated at about $750 million. International donors have pledged
$400 million. On Monday, President Clinton announced an additional
U.S. contribution of $78 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine, which gets about 40 percent of its electricity from
nuclear power plants, also hopes foreign nations will help build
two new atomic reactors to compensate for the loss of Chernobyl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1724 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000605.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Seeks New Red Cross Emblem  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Israel has balked at plans to create a neutral
third emblem for the Red Cross movement, meant to clear the way for
the Israeli society to join after more than 50 years, officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   All members of the International Committee of the Red Cross use
a red cross or, in Muslim countries, a red crescent as their
emblem.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's counterpart organization, Magen David Adom, uses a red
Star of David on a white flag -- which the Red Cross has refused to
sanction as a symbol for relief workers.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross leaders proposed adopting the new emblem that could be
used by all countries -- probably a red diamond framing a regional
symbol, such as the cross or crescent.
</P>
<P>
   But ''the Israelis have told us that they wish to make
amendments to the draft protocol,'' said Red Cross spokesman Chris
Bowers.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Magen David Adom, Dr. Moshe Mellul, said his
organization had serious reservations about the diamond -- which he
said signified flammable materials in some countries and a casino
in others.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not suitable for a humanitarian society,'' Mellul said
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also wanted the right to use the six-pointed Star of
David in its symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Resolution of the emblem problem would clear the way for the
Israeli society to be admitted as a voting member of the
International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies,
where it has held only observer status since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The international federation has arranged a conference Nov. 14
for its 176 member societies to vote on the new symbol. A
conference of the 188 nations of the Geneva Conventions will likely
be held in October to approve a new protocol to the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Magen David Adom http://www.magendavidadom.org
</P>
<P>
   American Red Cross http://www.redcross.org
</P>
<P>
   International Committee of the Red Cross http://www.icrc.org
</P>
<P>
   International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies
http://www.ifrc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
