<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Clash in Congo  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Even as it fought artillery duels with
Uganda, the Rwandan army said Monday it would complete its
withdrawal from the Congolese city of Kisangani and turn control
over to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan forces used heavy artillery and small-arms fire against
Rwandan soldiers who assembled in downtown Kisangani where they
waited for U.N. military observers to escort them out of the city,
Rwandan army spokesman Maj. Emmanuel Ndahiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross officials in Kisangani said four civilians were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   But Ndahiro insisted: ''We are on the path of withdrawal. We are
about to finalize it, unilaterally if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Uganda and Rwanda had fought in August and again in May in
Kisangani, but then agreed to pull back 60 miles and let the United
Nations take charge of the divided city, which is used by both
sides to resupply their troops in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The two neighbors sent armies into the Congo two years ago to
support a rebellion against President Laurent Kabila. But they
differed over how the war should be fought and which of the three
rebel groups to support.
</P>
<P>
   Their differences led to their clashes in Kisangani, the only
city in Congo where both armies have troops.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, two shells landed near the house used by U.N.
military observers in Kisangani, who moved to a local church, said
a U.N. military spokesman in the Congolese capital, Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Congo once involved five intervening nations and
three rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila and the rebels signed a peace deal last August, as did
Rwanda and Uganda and Kabila's allies from Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   A 5,537-strong U.N. force is supposed to protect the more than
100 unarmed military observers now deployed in the vast country to
oversee the cease-fire and the withdrawal of foreign troops. A
battalion was expected to arrive in Kisangani in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1736 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
