<DOCNO> APW20000605.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Rescue Six Kidnap Victims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Police killed three kidnappers in a
10-minute firefight Monday and rescued six people held hostage for
more than a month in a rural town in southeastern Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The shootout occurred when six heavily armed police officers
approached the kidnappers' hide-out in Socorro, 70 miles north of
Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   ''The kidnappers, who were armed with machine-guns and heavy
caliber weapons, opened fire as soon as they realized they had been
discovered,'' officer Amarildo Pedroso de Moraes said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting ended, police rushed into the small house and
found three kidnappers dead. They arrested another three who turned
themselves in, Moraes said.
</P>
<P>
   The six hostages -- three men and three women -- were unhurt and
''in relatively good condition after the ordeal.'' One police
officer received a bullet wound in his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   Moraes would not confirm media reports that said the kidnappers
had cut off part of one hostage's ear and sent it to his family to
pressure it to pay an undisclosed ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo Adriano de Oliveira, one of the dead kidnappers, was
believed to have taken part in last year's abduction of Wellington
de Camargo, the brother of country music stars Zeze di Camargo and
Luciano. Camargo was held for more than three months, and was freed
after his brothers paid a $300,000 ransom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1749 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000605.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Kidnap Victims Rescued in Brazil  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Police killed three kidnappers in a
10-minute firefight Monday and rescued six people held hostage for
more than a month in a rural town in southeastern Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The shootout occurred when six heavily armed police officers
approached the kidnappers' hide-out in Socorro, 70 miles north of
Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   ''The kidnappers, who were armed with machine-guns and heavy
caliber weapons, opened fire as soon as they realized they had been
discovered,'' officer Amarildo Pedroso de Moraes said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting ended, police rushed into the small house and
found three kidnappers dead. They arrested another three who turned
themselves in, Moraes said.
</P>
<P>
   The six hostages -- three men and three women -- were unhurt and
''in relatively good condition after the ordeal.'' One police
officer received a bullet wound in his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   Moraes would not confirm media reports that said the kidnappers
had cut off part of one hostage's ear and sent it to his family to
pressure it to pay an undisclosed ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo Adriano de Oliveira, one of the dead kidnappers, was
believed to have taken part in last year's abduction of Wellington
de Camargo, the brother of country music stars Zeze di Camargo and
Luciano. Camargo was held for more than three months, and was freed
after his brothers paid a $300,000 ransom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
