<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planes To Pay for US Airspace Use  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airplanes flying through U.S. airspace will be
charged for air traffic control services, even if they do not land
or take off here, the government said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new fees will take effect Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the U.S. government has not charged for such
flyovers, the Federal Aviation Administration said. Most other
countries impose such charges.
</P>
<P>
   Congress gave the FAA the right to require the payments in 1996,
but a federal court ruled in 1997 that the fees first announced
were not consistent with the law. That delayed the change until the
FAA could recalculate its costs for providing air traffic control
services.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, the agency said, a flight from Copenhagen,
Denmark to Rio de Janeiro, Brazil passes through airspace
controlled by France, Portugal, the United States, the Netherlands
Antilles and Venezuela, as well as that of Denmark and Brazil. Of
these, the United States is the only one not currently charging
overflight fees.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's new rule sets fees of $37.43 per 100 nautical miles
over land and $20.16 per 100 nautical miles over the ocean while
under U.S. air traffic control. A nautical mile is 1.15 regular
miles.
</P>
<P>
   No charges will be assessed on military and civilian aircraft
operated by the U.S. government or by foreign governments, and
users who accrue $250 or less in fees per month will not be
charged. There will also be no charges on Canada-to-Canada flights
that pass through U.S. airspace.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said it will send users monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said about 235,000 flights pass through U.S. airspace
annually and estimated that during the first year it will bill
airlines for $39.6 million in fees.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Aviation Administration site:
http://www.faa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
