<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 21; Nasdaq Up 8  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended an extremely quiet session with
mixed results Monday as investors took some profits from last
week's big gains but continued rewarding technology companies that
have strong growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 20.54 to close at
10,815.30.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
rose 8.38 to 3,821.76, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 9.63 to
1,467.63.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was very calm as investors captured some gains from a
strong, broad-based rally last week. The Nasdaq rose 19 percent
over the week, the index's biggest weekly gain in history and a
dramatic departure from the weakness it suffered in March and
April.
</P>
<P>
   The essential optimism that drove the market's rally last week
remained intact, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market's doing extremely well,'' said Edward Yardeni,
chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities. ''The summer rally
clearly is upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yardeni cautioned that the market may still struggle for
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may cover a lot of territory in a short period of time and
go sideways for a while,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the technology stocks that dominate the Nasdaq turned in
a mixed performance.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm fell $5.438 to $67.25. Over the weekend, China United
Telecommunications confirmed it won't use a mobile phone technology
designed by Qualcomm for at least three years. Speculation about
the China contract had heightened volatility in Qualcomm shares in
the past few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com fell $3.375 to $54.50, following a 15 percent gain on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba rose $10 to $80.50 after the company formed a partnership
with VeriSign Inc. and American Express to provide a card payment
processing function for online business-to-business transactions.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Advanced Micro Devices rose
$1.625 to $91.50. The company has introduced a souped-up version of
its Athlon computer chip and a new bargain brand; both products are
viewed as a challenge to industry leader Intel.
</P>
<P>
   IBM rose $4 to $112.438, helping to keep the Dow in positive
territory. Merrill Lynch analyst Steven Milunovich said that while
the company's second-quarter earnings may be fairly mediocre,
profit growth is accelerating and should provide for a strong
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Merger activity stimulated some trading. Primark rose $8.25 to
$37.25 after Thomson Corp. agreed to buy it for $842 million in
cash. Both companies are providers of professional and financial
information.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors were still reveling in last week's good
economic news. A stream of economic data showed a modest slowdown
in the economy, which many investors interpreted as a sign that the
Federal Reserve may not need to aggressively raise interest rates
to prevent a flareup of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is now a widespread perception that the Fed won't raise
rates at its June meeting, and perhaps that they're done for the
year,'' Yardeni said. ''It will be hard for them to justify raising
interest rates when there is evidence of a slowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the only economic report expected to move markets is
the Labor Department's Producer Price Index, due out on Friday.
With a dearth of news, the market may struggle to find direction,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dallas Federal Reserve President Robert McTeer said
there's little question that the Fed's six interest rate increases
in the past year are having the desired effect. But he cautioned
against placing too much stock in one month's figures.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, he said, ''are always all over the place and it
remains to be seen whether this is a fluke or signs of a changing
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.02
billion shares, compared with 1.39 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.27 to 513.30.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.4 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.4 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
fell 1.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.3 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
