<HEADLINE> Turkey, US Question Iran Defector  </HEADLINE>
By AYLA JEAN YACKLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- U.S. and Turkish agents were questioning
an Iranian defector who claims to have evidence that Tehran planned
and financed the bombings of Pam Am Flight 103 and a U.S. military
barracks in Saudi Arabia, reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The defector, who identified himself as Ahmad Behbahani, told
the CBS News program ''60 Minutes'' that he was a senior
intelligence official and has documents to prove his claim that
Iran was behind the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has not issued an official response to the claims. But the
hard-line daily Tehran Times claimed Monday that Behbahani is a
member of the outlawed Iranian opposition group Mujahedeen Khalq.
The Mujahedeen Khalq denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Two Libyans are on trial before a Scottish court in the
Netherlands for the 1998 bombing of the Pam Am jetliner over
Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people -- most of them
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Law experts said Behbahani's statements were unlikely to affect
the outcome of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 truck bombing of Khobar Towers in Saudi Arabia killed
19 U.S. Air Force personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's National Intelligence Agency confirmed that its agents
and agents of a foreign secret service had interrogated a man it
identified as Seyyid Behbahani. It did not identify the foreign
agency, but newspapers said that Behbahani was questioned by the
CIA. There was no official explanation for the discrepancies in the
first names, but an Iranian expert said Behbahani, as an
intelligence officer, traveled under different names.
</P>
<P>
   ''Behbahani, who was seen as suspicious, has been interviewed by
our agency,'' the Turkish intelligence agency said in a statement
carried by the Anatolia news agency. ''The person claims that Iran
organized some terrorist actions in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In his initial testimonies, he said he worked for a while at
the Iranian Intelligence Ministry and escaped from Evin prison
where he was imprisoned in 1998 for spying on behalf of a foreign
country,'' the statement said. Evin prison is in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   The National Intelligence Agency said Behbahani contacted ''60
Minutes'' before coming to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Behbahani arrived in the eastern city of Van on March 7 after
crossing the Iranian border and applied for asylum at the local
bureau of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am in a difficult position. I fled to Turkey because they
were going to kill me,'' the Turkish newspaper Hurriyet quoted
Behbahani as telling UNHCR officials. ''I want America to grant me
asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy in Ankara and the UNHCR would not comment about
Behbahani. In Washington, the State Department said it still
supports an official dialogue with Iran despite the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In the ''60 Minutes'' report aired Sunday, Behbahani said Iran
planned the Pan Am bombing to avenge a U.S. Navy cruiser's mistaken
downing of an Iranian passenger plane in early 1988. He said he
recruited a radical Palestinian terrorist living in Syria, then
imported and trained Libyan operatives to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   According to ''60 Minutes,'' Behbahani also claimed that Iran
was behind the 1994 bombing attack of a Jewish community center in
Buenos Aires, Argentina, that killed 86 people.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Reza Nourizadeh, an Iranian columnist at the London-based
Kayhan weekly, told The Associated Press that Behbahani was a
deputy intelligence minister and had ''slipped into Turkey after he
realized that a car accident in which he was involved was really an
assassination attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran's reformist President Mohammad Khatami ordered a purge of
the Intelligence Ministry after it admitted ''rogue'' agents were
behind the killings of five dissidents in the fall of 1998, curbing
the powers of Iranian secret agents.
</P>
<P>
   Nourizadeh said Behbahani was a right-hand man of former
intelligence minister Ali Fallahian and was in danger since he told
an investigative committee that his former boss had ordered the
dissidents' murders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1816 </TRAILER>
