<DOCNO> APW20000605.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Camaign Finance Standards Set  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Money is pouring into politics as never
before. Thirty-seven House candidates have already raised at least
$1 million -- a fourfold increase over last time. And the Democratic
and Republican parties have almost doubled their intake of soft
money since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''Will there be a record that hasn't been broken by the end of
the cycle?'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center
for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan group that studies money and
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Republican nominee George W. Bush set the pace by raising more
than $84 million so far to shatter all presidential fund-raising
records.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission reported Monday that 37 House
candidates had raised at least $1 million between Jan. 1, 1999, and
March 31, 2000, compared with just seven during the same 15-month
period two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats need just six seats to recapture the House, and
both parties and campaign contributors are focusing on a handful of
competitive races that will decide who holds the majority.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes two Republicans who presented impeachment
evidence against President Clinton to the Senate:
</P>
<P>
   --The top House fund-raiser, Rep. Jim Rogan, R-Calif., faces a
tough challenge from California state Sen. Adam Schiff in a
district Rogan won with just 51 percent of the vote in 1998. Rogan
raised $3.8 million through March 31 -- more than twice the $1.4
million raised for his entire 1998 campaign. Schiff raised $1.9
million to lead all challengers.
</P>
<P>
   --Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., who raised $1.6 million for his
successful 1998 campaign, already has raised $1.8 million for his
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   One of the targeted Democrats, Rep. Shelley Berkley, D-Nev., who
raised $1.3 million for her last race, raised $1.2 million through
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because people believe there are only 20 or 25 seriously
competitive races out there, each one of them is their own private
Fort Knox,'' Democratic consultant Peter Fenn said. ''Money is
flowing into the handful of races in unprecedented amounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who fail to raise money early may have trouble later
because so many donors have already been tapped out, Republican
fund-raiser Carolyn Machado said. ''As you get further along in the
season, those dollars dry up.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, 22 House candidates reported having at least $1
million in the bank as of March 31, double the number of two years
ago. They were led by Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., who since has taken
his $3.5 million bankroll and entered the U.S. Senate race against
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate Lazio replaced, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, raised more money than anyone else, $19.3 million.
Clinton was next at $12.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Wall Street millionaire Jon Corzine, seeking the
Democratic nomination for U.S. Senate in New Jersey, was third on
the list with $11 million, most of it his own money. Since March
31, he's reached deeper and wound up spending an estimated $33
million in advance of Tuesday's primary, breaking the old record of
$30 million for a Senate race set by California Republican Michael
Huffington in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Senate candidates who raised more than $1 million
through March 31 increased 25 percent between 1998 and 2000, from
40 two years ago to 50 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, House and Senate candidates raised $463 million, up
$125 million over the same period two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The political parties are raising more as well. Contributions of
unregulated soft money to the national Democratic and Republican
parties have almost doubled since 1996, the last presidential
election year.
</P>
<P>
   From Jan. 1, 1999 through last March 31, the GOP took in $86.4
million in soft money -- unlimited donations from corporations,
unions and individuals not subject to federal election laws. That's
a 93 percent increase over the $44.7 million the party raised
during the same period in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic committees, meanwhile, raised $77 million in soft
money, up 94 percent from the $39.7 million raised during the same
period in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   The parties have been helped by the booming economy and the
growing number of high-tech millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's just a lot more money out there,'' Republican
consultant Eddie Mahe said. ''You've got thousands and thousands of
multimillionaires in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, which boosted
its soft money donations from $3.4 million in 1995-96 to $21.9
million in 1999-2000, was to add to its totals Monday at a
fund-raiser celebrating the 70th birthday of New York Rep. Charles
Rangel.
</P>
<P>
   With a top ticket of $100,000, the event was expected to raise
$3 million for the DCCC, the most the committee, which contributes
to Democratic candidates for the House, has ever taken in at a
fund-raiser outside of Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
