<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Clarifies Estate Taxes Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Associated Press reported June 4 that a
married couple can effectively get a $1.3 million exemption in 2000
from federal estate taxes, or twice the $675,000 exemption for an
individual.
</P>
<P>
   That is true, but it is not automatic. Certain estate planning
steps must be taken first by the couple, such as creation of a
credit shelter trust.
</P>
<P>
   An example: A couple has $1.3 million in assets when the man
dies. He leaves $675,000 to his wife, which is exempt from tax
because they were married. The remaining $675,000, also exempt from
tax under the man's individual exemption, goes into a trust for the
heirs.
</P>
<P>
   When the wife dies, her $675,000 share goes to the heirs
tax-free because of her individual exemption. The trust also goes
to the heirs without tax because it is considered to have already
been exposed to tax -- even though the man's exemption applied at
the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 1824 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
