<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Observers in Georgia Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) -- Kidnappers in Georgia's separatist
region of Abkhazia freed four U.N. observers Monday, after taking
them hostage for ransom last week.
</P>
<P>
   The observers -- two Danes, a Briton, and an Abkhazian -- were
released without the U.N. paying ransom, said U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard in New York. Raul Khadzhinba, head of Abkhazia's Security
Service, also said no ransom was paid.
</P>
<P>
   The observers were abducted Thursday in the remote Kodor Gorge,
the only part of separatist Abkhazia still under Georgian control.
A fifth member of the group, an Abkhazian, was released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The two Danes and the Briton were flown to Tbilisi, the Georgian
capital, on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian mass media said the kidnappers had demanded $300,000
for the hostages' release.
</P>
<P>
   Danish officials said in a statement that the released Danes
were Maj. Thomas Rosenquist, 41, and Capt. Kaj S. Laursen, 21. The
Briton was John Fulford, who works with the Halo Trust de-mining
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Abkhazian separatists drove out Georgian government forces
during a 1992-93 war and have run almost all of the province since
then. The two sides reached a cease-fire in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
