<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marines Announce Osprey Tests  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Marine Corps resumed flights of the MV-22
Osprey, the hybrid helicopter-airplane that came under severe
scrutiny after one crashed April 8 in Arizona and killed 19
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines announced that flight tests were restarted Monday at
the Naval Air Warfare Center Weapons Division at China Lake, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Osprey to come off the production line, initially
sent to Marine Corps Air Station New River at Camp Lejeune, N.C.,
will join three other Ospreys at China Lake so they can fly
together on missions designed to evaluate the Osprey's readiness to
join the Marine Corps' active air fleet. Evaluation began last
November but was interrupted when the Osprey crashed upon approach
to Marana Airport in Tucson, Ariz., in April.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation is scheduled for completion in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines announced last month that mechanical failure was
ruled out as a cause of the crash, although the investigation is
continuing. It was the deadliest air disaster for the Marines since
22 died in a helicopter crash in South Korea in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
