<HEADLINE> Peru Prosecutor Confirms Conspiracy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A special prosecutor on Monday confirmed the
existence of a conspiracy to forge signatures to help register
President Alberto Fujimori's candidacy for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutor Mirtha Trabucco -- who is widely perceived as
loyal to Fujimori -- told a special congressional panel that after a
97-day investigation, the only culprits who had been charged were
the two young whistle-blowers who first revealed the fraud, as well
as their mother.
</P>
<P>
   Trabucco said she could not be ''rushed'' into filing additional
charges, but that her investigation ''will determine if there are
others responsible'' for the forgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori coasted to a guaranteed victory in the May 28
presidential runoff after his challenger, economist Alejandro
Toledo, boycotted the vote, alleging the election was rigged.
</P>
<P>
   Independent monitors, who refused to observe the runoff because
it failed to meet basic international standards of fairness,
complained throughout the campaign that Fujimori's government was
dragging its feet on the forgery investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's leading newspaper, El Comercio, broke the story in
February, reporting that Fujimori's re-election campaign had hired
more than 400 people to systematically forge about 1 million
qualifying signatures, copied from the 1998 municipal election
voter rolls.
</P>
<P>
   The reports were based on information from Carlos and Marita
Rodriguez, a brother and sister who copied signatures, and who
later offered to testify. Their mother, who also claimed to take
part in the fraud, came forward a short time later. They have not
been arrested and Trabucco did not specify what penalty they could
face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
