<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haiti Rejects OAS Vote Findings  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL NORTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- A Haiti election official is
rejecting a claim by the Organization of American States that
Haiti's method of determining the winners of its parliamentary
elections was invalid.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS said Friday it found flaws in how the winning
percentages in the May 21 local and legislative elections were
calculated. It was the latest hitch in an election seen as a last
chance for democracy in this impoverished Caribbean nation of 8
million people.
</P>
<P>
   OAS mission chief Orlando Marville asked the council to
recalculate the percentage of votes for all candidates to preserve
the election's credibility. A recalculation could force several
declared Senate winners to run in a second round of voting.
</P>
<P>
   Electoral Council official Macajou Medard said on state
Television Nationale late Sunday that the head of the OAS elections
observer mission had no right ''to order'' any changes. The council
will issue a statement formally rejecting the criticism, Medard
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the OAS said Monday it was not trying to usurp the power of
local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are certain things being misinterpreted or
misread,'' said Elizabeth Spehar, executive coordinator of the OAS
unit for promotion of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   According to partial returns, former President Jean-Bertrand
Aristide's Lavalas Family party seized control of Haiti's Senate,
sweeping 16 of 17 seats at stake.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the U.S. Embassy in Haiti sided with the OAS.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States exhorts the provisional electoral council to
correct the problems the Organization of American States
identified,'' it said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Marville didn't deny that most voters cast their ballots for
Aristide candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But his request for a recalculation of winning percentages cast
suspicion on a first-round Lavalas landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian law says that to win in the first round, a candidate
must get 50 percent plus 1 vote. If not, the top two finishers meet
in a second round, set for June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Under Haitian election law, officials count all the ballots
cast, and then discard all but the four top vote-getters. Medard
conceded that while this could change the winning percentages, it
does not change the amount of votes won by each candidate. However,
he said, foreign observers had no objections to similar procedures
in 1990, 1995 and 1997 legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
   Marville ''showed lack of respect not only to the electoral
council but to the country and every single Haitian,'' said Medard.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti declared winners in at least eight Senate races where no
one won more than 50 percent, said Ernest Colon of the opposition
Christian Movement for a New Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti hasn't had a Parliament since January 1999. President Rene
Preval shut it down after an 18-month standoff with opposition
senators.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide was elected in 1990 and overthrown in a 1991 coup. U.S.
troops restored him to power in 1994. Haitian law barred him from
seeking a consecutive term in 1995. He is expected to run again for
the presidency is expected to win easily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 2002 </TRAILER>
