<DOCNO> APW20000605.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher Tax Exemption Is Rejected  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER KERR
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis' proposal to exempt
public school teachers from the state income tax was unanimously
rejected Monday by legislative budget negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had said the $545 million plan was a pioneering effort to
ease California's teacher shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, that saves $500 million,'' conference committee
chairman, Democratic Sen. Steve Peace, said to laughter from the
panel as the proposal was voted down.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's three Democrats and three Republicans instead
approved a package of improved retirement benefits and tax cuts,
including a maximum $500 credit for teachers who buy classroom
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor last month proposed the income tax break
for the state's 283,000 teachers as part of his plan to spend an
estimated budget surplus of $12.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to address a teacher shortage in California and to
draw high-quality teachers to the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal drew immediate and near-universal opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said setting tax policy by occupation was a dangerous
precedent that would prompt other public employees, such as police
or firefighters, to seek similar exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   The state's biggest teachers' union, the California Teachers
Association, did not endorse it. The second-largest, the California
Federation of Teachers, opposed it, saying the money could be
better spent on higher salaries for beginning teachers or improved
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokeswoman Hilary McLean said the governor has not given
up and is still negotiating with legislative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just round one,'' McLean said. ''Governor Davis
continues to believe that all 34 million Californians will benefit
if teachers receive the extraordinary recognition he proposes
through the tax code.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
