<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, June 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Strips Pinochet of Immunity
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A court on Monday announced its decision to strip
Gen. Augusto Pinochet of his immunity from prosecution, leaving Chile's former
dictator facing a long legal battle over the human rights abuses committed under
his rule. Pinochet's defense team said it would appeal the ruling. The Santiago
Court of Appeals voted 13-9 on May 23 to remove the congressional immunity
Pinochet enjoys as a senator for life. He faces 110 lawsuits filed on behalf of
those killed or missing during his 17-year rule.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chernobyl Nuclear Plant To Close
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Ukraine President Leonid Kuchma on Monday ordered the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant closed, drawing praise from President Clinton, who
provided $80 million in American aid to close the plant forever. The April 26,
1986 accident spread radioactive material over much of Europe. The Ukrainian
government has blamed the disaster for at least 8,000 deaths, including 31
killed immediately, many more killed in the massive cleanup operation and others
who later died of cancer and other radiation-related illnesses. The plant will
close on Dec. 15, Kuchma said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Solomon Islands PM Taken Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- Rebels seized the prime minister of the
Solomon Islands on Monday on Guadalcanal. Phone lines and air links to the
Solomons were cut as the rebels from a shadowy group calling itself the Malaita
Eagle Force set up roadblocks around the capital. The Malaita Eagle gunmen
demanded the resignation of Prime Minister Bartholemew Ulufa'alu, according to
Australian and New Zealand officials. The apparent coup attempt was the second
in the South Pacific in weeks -- with armed rebels in Fiji still holding the
deposed prime minister and more than 30 other people seized in a raid on
Parliament on May 19.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Death-Row Inmate Wins New Hearing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Casting doubt on the fate of at least eight other condemned
inmates in Texas, the U.S. Supreme Court threw out a killer's death sentence
today after prosecutors conceded that the penalty was based in part on the fact
that he is Hispanic. The court ordered a new sentencing hearing for Victor Hugo
Saldano, convicted of murdering a man for his wallet and watch in a Dallas
suburb in 1996.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Eyes Territorial Concessions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- As Secretary of State Madeleine Albright sought to speed up
peacemaking, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Monday that Israel's
security depends on a ''settlement presence'' along the Jordan Valley. Barak
also suggested he was inclined to sweeten his territorial offers to the
Palestinians in a drive to conclude a final accord over such sensitive problems
as Jerusalem's future and how much land Yasser Arafat will have for his
Palestinian state.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Curbs Grandparents' Rights
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court gave new vigor to parents' ''fundamental
right'' to raise their families free from government interference, ruling today
that Washington state went too far in letting grandparents and others seek
visitation. ''So long as a parent adequately cares for his or her children ...
there will normally be no reason for the state to inject itself into the private
realm of the family,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote in the court's main
opinion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gates: Next Web Phase More Personal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The next phase of the Internet will allow users to
gather information from multiple places and control the manner and timing of how
they receive it, Microsoft chairman Bill Gates said today. Microsoft, the
world's software leader, is prepared to provide the tools to get there, Gates
told 14,000 computer industry workers at the four-day Microsoft Tech-Ed
conference in Orlando. Gates pledged $2 billion over three years for education
and support programs for software developers and information technology
professionals who will use Microsoft's next generation of technology.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 21; Nasdaq Is Up 8
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended an extremely quiet session with mixed results
as investors took some profits from last week's sharp gains but continued
rewarding technology companies with strong growth prospects. The Dow Jones
industrial average was up 20.54 at 10,815.30. On the NYSE, decliners led
advancers 1,636-1,331. The Nasdaq composite index rose 8.38 to 3,821.76.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Braves Blame Rocker Demotion on Pitching
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Braves officials insist that John Rocker's demotion
to the minors is unrelated to a confrontation he had yesterday with the reporter
who wrote the story in which the Atlanta reliever disparaged gays, minorities
and foreigners. Rocker was fined ''a substantial amount'' for the confrontation
with Sports Illustrated reporter Jeff Pearlman, said manager Bobby Cox. General
manager John Schuerholz says Rocker was optioned because he was not pitching
well. Rocker has walked 25 batters in just 18 1/3 innings this season.
</P>
