<DOCNO> APW20000605.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Eyes More Fed Services Online  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN MILLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Al Gore promised on Monday that as
president he would have nearly all federal services online by 2003
in a ''second American Revolution'' linking the people and their
government via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He raised a vision of buyers competing for government business
via Internet auctions. And he called for the creation of a
''g-bay,'' similar to e-bay auctions, for selling off government
equipment that is no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   Many states, cities and counties already provide some services
online, as does the federal government, including electronic filing
of taxes. But Gore said in a speech at North Carolina State
University that he is aiming to break down barriers between
departments and make them more accessible to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ''The power of government should not be locked away in
Washington but put at your services -- no further away than your
keyboard,'' the Democratic presidential contender said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that under his plan, people could use the Internet to
get information about Social Security benefits, to apply for a home
loan through the Federal Home Administration, to report a crime or
to find the health plan that would work best for them.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted government ''online -- so you don't have to
stand in line.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said that a wired-in government could help
''an electorate that is too often alienated and often feels
voiceless in a system corroded by special interests and powerless
to make change.'' He did not mention online voting.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics fear the security of casting ballots via the
Internet, but Arizona's March primary was conducted successfully
online.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he plans to discuss later this week digital keys,
combinations and other ways to keep such data secure in order to
protect privacy of people corresponding with the government.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say how much his plan would cost but contended it
would save billions in the long run. Gore spokesman Chris Lehane
said later that implementing it would cost about $100 million,
which would be paid through budget surpluses over the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would require government agencies to file progress
reports online and that interested citizens could respond via
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ''With your help, as president, I will lead a second American
Revolution -- to make our self-government far less costly, far more
effective and far more relevant to every American,'' Gore told
about 100 teachers and students at the university's Centennial
campus in the heart of the state's Research Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said the nation's investment in information
technology, which now accounts for about one-third of the country's
economic growth, should double. Gore and Commerce Secretary William
M. Daley released a report showing that such spending has grown
from $243 billion in 1995 to $510 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is recognized for his interest in technical
subjects, though he also has been subjected to ridicule for telling
CNN last March that he ''took the initiative in creating the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has been increasing its online business,
including an estimated 35 million income tax returns filed
electronically this year -- a 20 percent increase over the previous
year. Nearly 30 percent of all tax returns were filed on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Gore gave the commencement speech at Tarboro
High School, which sheltered refugees from Hurricane Floyd's
floodwaters last September.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are American heroes,'' Gore said. Speaking before a crowd
of about 2,400 in the school football stadium, he described the 136
graduating seniors as ''sterling successes by any measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd dumped 20 inches of rain on eastern North Carolina last
September, and the resulting flooding was blamed for at least 51
deaths and $6 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recounted how some of the graduates lost all of their
possessions, yet showed up at the high school to ask how they could
help.
</P>
<P>
   ''You made a difference in reaching out to others instead of
just caring for yourself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore flew to New York, where he attended a record
$3-million dinner and reception for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, which assists Democratic candidates for the
House. U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton and House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., attended the reception at The
Supper Club, which doubled as a 70th birthday celebration for Rep.
Charles Rangel of New York, the top Democrat on the House Ways and
Means Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
