<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Gretzky Gets Honorary Doctor of Laws at University of Alberta
<TEXT>
<P>
   	   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky became Dr. Wayne Gretzky
in a ceremony Monday that saw graduates break ranks to kiss him,
shake his hand and jump in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   ''I say to you kids graduating today, don't forget what got you
there. Don't forget your family. Don't forget your grassroots and
the community that you are in,'' Gretzky, dressed in a red gown
with white trim, told graduates at the University of Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   He received a standing ovation as the three-tiered auditorium
shimmered in the blue and white pops of flash bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   No. 99 received a doctor of laws for his contribution to sport
and community.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he spoke, he was the center of attention as
graduates, prior to receiving their degrees, broke out of the line
to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   ------
HRDC Withdraws 10 Times Too Much Money From Widow
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Advocates are calling for an apology and a policy
change after the Human Resources Department withdrew 10 times too
much money from an elderly widow's bank account without telling
her.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Parry of Ottawa, only learned the federal department had
dipped into her funds to recover her dead husband's old age
security benefits after the bank mailed her copies of the
government claim form and a bank draft for $8,399.68.
</P>
<P>
   The sum should have been $839.68 or two months' overpayment. But
poor paperwork and bad handwriting by a bureaucrat at the
department's income security programs branch left the impression
the amount owing was 10 times more.
</P>
<P>
   An HRDC official said it's not department policy to go to the
bank without first trying to recover money through the client. She
blamed an administrative error for the foul-up.
</P>
<P>
   ------
British Columbia Attorney General Orders Corrections Probe
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- British Columbia's attorney
general has ordered an independent investigation into how seven
Chinese migrants managed to bolt from a detention facility.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it appropriate ... to review the circumstances that
occurred here so we can both find out what happened and prevent it
from happening,'' Andrew Petter said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Investigations Inspections and Standards office is to report
back with recommendations to Petter's ministry and the British
Columbia Corrections Branch, which is housing the migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Police captured six of the seven men but are still in pursuit of
one man, believed to be hiding in the dense and dangerous bush near
the Prince George Regional Correctional Center about 500 kilometers
north of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The escapees are among 168 people being detained since their
illegal arrival last summer on a decrepit ship off British
Columbia's coast.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Man Convicted Of Murder For the Fourth Time This Year
</P>
<P>
   SAINT JOHN, New Brunswick (AP) -- Michael Wayne McGray has been
convicted of murder for the fourth time this year in the ongoing
story of a man's chilling urge to kill.
</P>
<P>
   McGray, a Nova Scotia-born drifter who has claimed
responsibility for 16 slayings across North America, appeared
briefly in court Monday and pleaded guilty to the 1987 stabbing
death of Saint John resident Mark Gibbons.
</P>
<P>
   McGray, 34, sullen, unshaven and with his feet shackled, said
little during his appearance. He told Justice Hugh McLellan of the
New Brunswick Court of Queen's Bench he was guilty of second-degree
murder and that he had no statement or explanation.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to life in prison, which will run concurrent to
the life sentences he's already serving for the first-degree
murders of a woman in Moncton, New Brunswick, in 1998 and two men
in Montreal in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He is not eligible for parole for 25 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
