<HEADLINE> Notes From Monday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressINTERLEAGUE:
Yankees-Expos:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: RHP Ramiro Mendoza was scratched from his start
against the Expos because of pain in his right shoulder. David
Cone, who pitched a perfect game against the Expos last July 18,
started in Mendoza's place. Cone was originally scheduled to face
Montreal's Javier Vazquez on Tuesday in what would have been a
rematch of the starters in Cone's perfect game. ... The Yankees
plan to use a reliever to start in Cone's place on Tuesday,
depending on who pitches Monday night. Jason Grimsley has made two
starts this year and Mike Stanton started once last season for New
York. ... 2B Chuck Knoblauch was also taken out of the starting
lineup before the game with a strained left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: RHP Dustin Hermanson made his first start since moving
to the bullpen in mid-May to replace injured closer Ugueth Urbina.
... LHP Steve Kline tied a team record Sunday by saving his fourth
straight game. Kline joined Claude Raymond, John Wetteland, Mel
Rojas -- who did it twice -- and Ugueth Urbina. Urbina saved four
straight last May 26-30. ... Kline and Hermanson have combined for
eight saves since Urbina injured his right elbow May 12.
Red Sox-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: OF Carl Everett, second on the team with a .324 batting
average, didn't start. Everett, a former Marlins player, has a
10-game hitting streak. ... OF Darren Lewis, the only Red Sox
player to have faced Marlins starter Reid Cornelius, doubled off
him to open the game. ... 1B Brian Daubach flipped his bat into the
stands not once but twice in the same at-bat. He had a bat boy
retrieve the first one, but when the second one came on a
strikeout, he let the fan keep it.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: OF Mark Kotsay hit three fly balls near the fence
Sunday against Toronto. Manager John Boles is confident similar
swings from Kotsay will result in home runs next season. ''I don't
think he's done maturing yet. He's still growing and he's still got
room on his frame for some muscle.'' ... Boles has just about
stopped looking at the numbers of his young players against
opposing pitchers. ''We don't have numbers against anybody.'' ...
The Marlins demoted RHP Vladimir Nunez (0-6, 8.35 ERA) to Triple-A
Calgary and reinstated OF Mark Smith from the 15-day DL.
Orioles-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Manager Mike Hargrove rejoined the team. He missed
two games in Montreal while attending his son Andy's high school
graduation in Cleveland. ... Mike Mussina made his first start ever
at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The Mets recalled OF Jason Tyner from Triple-A Norfolk
and designated IF-OF Ryan McGuire for assignment. Tyner, 23, was
immediately put into the starting lineup, leading off and playing
left field. ''I think I'll be all right, once I get all the
butterflies out of my stomach,'' Tyner said. Said Mets GM Steve
Phillips: ''He gets to face Mike Mussina tonight, then Scott
Erickson and then Roger Clemens and Andy Pettitte. Welcome to the
big leagues.'' ... RHP Rick Reed, who missed Friday's scheduled
start against Tampa Bay because of a strained abdominal muscle on
his left side, is set to pitch Tuesday.
Devil Rays-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: The Devil Rays are 0-11 this year when a left-hander
starts and 21-60 since the start of the 1998 season, the worst in
the majors. They are not scheduled to see a left-handed starter in
their series with Philadelphia. ... DH Jose Canseco is scheduled to
come off of the DL on Friday. He was on the DL with a bruised heel.
... Devil Rays fans were able to follow the entire draft online,
complete with comments from scouting director Dan Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Mike Lieberthal, who hit three home runs in the
last two games, was rested. ... Before Monday's games, Phillies'
opponents had a .541 winning percentage, highest in the majors.
White Sox-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Frank Thomas, who sat out Sunday after playing the
first 54 games, was back in the lineup at first base. He was in a
2-for-19 slump. ... Thomas needed to score one more run to become
the sixth active player with 300 homers, 1,000 runs scored, 1,000
RBIs and 1,000 walks. The others are Harold Baines, Barry Bonds,
Fred McGriff, Mark McGwire and Cal Ripken Jr. ... The White Sox
didn't play the Reds last season. Instead, the Reds traded their
series for an extra three-game series against Cleveland. ... Ray
Durham, who led off the first interleague game at Cinergy Field
with a homer in 1997, led off Monday's game with a triple. ...
Chicago chose Stanford OF Joe Borchard with the 12th overall pick
in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: OF Alex Ochoa was back in the clubhouse for the
first time since he was taken to a hospital last Wednesday for an
appendectomy. He's on the DL and can't work out yet. ... RHP Mark
Wohlers threw one inning for Triple-A Louisville, allowing one hit
and one walk and striking out two Scranton batters. He had only
thrown at Class A until Monday as part of his rehab from
reconstructive elbow surgery. He'll pitch for Louisville again on
Thursday. ... RHP Osvaldo Fernandez will miss his next scheduled
start because of a sore elbow, jammed when he hit a line drive
Sunday. ... The Reds chose high school SS David Espinosa with the
23rd overall pick in the first round.
Indians-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: The Indians entered the three-game series Monday in
Milwaukee with an all-time record of 197-197 against the Brewers in
the past 30 seasons. ... RHP Paul Rigdon is scheduled to start a
30-day rehabilitation assignment at Triple-A Buffalo. He'll start
Tuesday in Buffalo against Indianapolis. ... The Indians have used
the DL 12 times this season for 11 players. OF Manny Ramirez
(strained left hamstring) is on the DL for the first time in his
career. ... Chuck Finley (4-4) will make his 12th start of the
season Tuesday. He's second in the NL with 82 strikeouts in 75.2
innings.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers selected 18-year-old OF Dave Krynzel of
Henderson, Nev., with the 11th pick of the first round of the
draft. Krynzel is batting .438 with five home runs and 31 RBI this
season for Green Valley High School. ... The Brewers, who opened a
three-game series with Cleveland, were 2-1 against the Indians in
1999. ... Brewers wives will auction the ''Turn Back the Clock''
uniforms to be worn by Milwaukee on Wednesday night. Proceeds will
go to Brewers Charities. ... Miller Park, being built just beyond
the outfield bleachers of County Stadium, is 80 percent complete.
The first game will be played in the retractable-roofed stadium in
298 days.
Twins-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins are batting .204 with seven doubles, two
home runs and eight RBI in their three interleague games, all
losses. Though Twins pitchers have hit .333 in those games, they
have never hit a home run in interleague play. In fact, the last
Twins pitcher to hit a home run was Jim Kaat June 11, 1972, vs.
Cleveland. ... The Twins have fewer home runs than any team in
baseball with a team total of 43 before Monday. That included 25 on
the road before entering home-run friendly Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Moises Alou has been out eight days with a left quad
muscle strain and probably won't return before Wednesday. Manager
Larry Dierker said Alou worked out lightly Monday and will do so
again Tuesday before the team makes a decision on his availability.
Dierker says Alou could have been used as a pinch-hitter over the
weekend but no situation with runners on base presented itself.
''He could have knocked somebody in, limped down to first base and
then got a pinch runner to run for him,'' Dierker said. ''But
without men on base, it wasn't worth pinch hitting him.'' ... The
Astros say the first-round draft pick Robert Stiehl started only
one game in his brief career as a pitcher at El Camino (Calif.)
Junior College doesn't concern them. Stiehl, normally a catcher and
closer who often caught eight innings of games this year and
pitched the ninth innings, has a 91-to-96 mph fastball and a strong
curve. Astros director of scouting David Lakey said the club knows
plenty about Stiehl. ''We have a club team he pitched for in the
winter in L.A.,'' Lakey said. ''We saw him quite a bit then. He has
an above average fastball and a good curve and if he comes up with
a third pitch, we don't see any reason why he can't make it to the
big leagues.''
Royals-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Before the game, the Royals placed 2B Carlos Febles
on the 15-day DL with a strained left shoulder. Febles was injured
diving for a ball in the 11th inning at Pittsburgh on Sunday. The
Royals called up INF Ray Holbert, who batted .264 with one home run
and 15 RBIs in 40 games for Triple-A Omaha. ... The interleague
series marked the return of former Cardinals closer Ricky Bottalico
to St. Louis. He was 3-7 with a 4.91 ERA and 20 saves last year and
wasn't offered a contract. ''I didn't give them a real big reason
to keep me,'' Bottalico said. ''So you can't be bitter.'' ... The
three-game interleague series completed a 32-game stretch during
which the Royals had only six games at home. They open a nine-game
homestand on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Garrett Stephenson was named NL pitcher of the month
for May, when he was 5-0 with a 1.42 ERA. Stephenson threw two
consecutive complete games, one of them his first career shutout.
The last Cardinals pitcher to be honored was Bob Tewksbury in April
1994. ... OF Ray Lankford was out of the lineup for the second
straight game with a strained left hamstring, and might be out of
the lineup for a few more games. ''I definitely want to be out
there, but you've got to be cautionary,'' Lankford said. ''You
don't want to make the situation worse.'' ... Reliever Jesse Orosco
makes his third rehab start Tuesday for Triple-A Memphis. Each of
the first two outings lasted 12 pitches for Orosco, a specialist at
retiring left-handed batters.
Dodgers-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: When Los Angeles lost 8-7 Sunday in their series
finale against Anaheim, it marked the first time this season that
the Dodgers lost a game in which they led by four runs or more. The
Dodgers led 4-0 after the first inning and 7-3 in the sixth. ...
Eric Karros hit the 227th homer of his career Sunday, leaving him
one short of Ron Cey for fourth place on the Dodgers home run list.
... The Dodgers used their first-round pick in Monday's draft to
selected RHP Ben Diggins, who was 10-4 with a 3.83 ERA in 17 games
for Arizona State this season. The 6-foot-7 pitcher struck out 127
in 113 innings with a fastball consistently clocked at 95 mph.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: For the first time in franchise history, Texas selected a
catcher in the first round of the baseball draft. The Rangers took
Scott Heard from Rancho Bernardino High in San Diego with the 25th
overall pick. AL MVP Ivan Rodriguez, who has won eight Gold Gloves
as the Rangers catcher, wasn't even drafted, much less taken in the
first round. He was signed by the Rangers as a non-drafted free
agent in 1988. ... OF Gabe Kapler, on the DL since May 4 with a
partial tear of his right quadriceps muscle, began a three-game
rehabilitation stint with Double-A Tulsa on Monday. Texas manager
Johnny Oates said Kapler looked good in a Monday morning workout at
The Ballpark in Arlington before he flew to El Paso for the three
games. If all goes well, Kapler will return to the Rangers lineup
as the starter in center field for Friday's game at Colorado. He
began the season in right field, but will move to center to replace
rookie Ruben Mateo, who is out for the season after breaking his
leg last Friday night.
Tigers-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Juan Gonzalez was out of the Tigers lineup on Monday.
He drove a foul ball off his already-sore left foot in Sunday's
game against the Cubs. Tigers manager Phil Garner waited to post a
lineup until he was sure of Gonzalez's availability. ... Coming to
generic Three Rivers Stadium was a major letdown for the Tigers
after spending their first weekend in Wrigley Field. Some of the
Tigers were in awe of Wrigley. First baseman Rob Fick was so taken
with the place that he brought family members on the field after
the game to pose for photos. Fick said he always had a fondness for
Boston's Fenway Park but, ''this blows them all away.''
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Kevin Young, the Pirates' former cleanup hitter, was
batting sixth in Monday's lineup. Young is in a 1-for-19 slump that
has dropped his average to .239. He was dropped to fifth a few
weeks ago. John Vander Wal replaced him the No. 5 spot in Monday's
game. ... Jimmy Anderson will make his first start since May 28 on
Tuesday. Anderson's future in the rotation and on the major league
roster are uncertain because he's 0-3 with a 7.47 ERA since getting
his only win over the Mets on April 15. Anderson's biggest problem
is the first inning -- he's given up runs in the first inning in
each of his last six starts.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Diamondbacks-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Randy Johnson said there were no problems with his
shoulder Monday when he played catch, the first time he's thrown
since his last start. The 1999 NL Cy Young winner was scheduled to
start Monday against the Cubs, but he skipped it after experiencing
tightness in his pitching shoulder. He had a cortisone injection
last Thursday. ''It was fine,'' Johnson said after playing catch
for 10 minutes. ''I'll try to throw catch tomorrow again, and then
Wednesday I'll throw on the side. That'll be the real test.''
Johnson (9-1) said he hopes to be back this weekend, when the
Diamondbacks play Anaheim. ''Shooting for Friday, I guess,'' he
said. ... Greg Colbrunn was back in the lineup Monday night after
missing Sunday's game. Colbrunn was hit in the elbow and arm
Saturday. ... Before the game, the Diamondbacks called up INF Danny
Klassen from Triple-A Tucson and optioned Nelson Figueroa to
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Cubs manager Don Baylor was thinking small when he made
out his lineup card for Monday's game. That's small as in short.
Chad Meyers, listed generously at 6-feet, was at second and Augie
Ojeda, who is 5-foot-8, was at short. ''I've got the shortest
lineup I've ever had in my life,'' Baylor said before the game,
laughing. ''Some scrappers out there.'' ... Despite a 2-4 record so
far in this nine-game homestand, the Cubs starting pitchers have
averaged almost 7 2-3 innings and have a 2.82 ERA. If the Cubs
could get some offense, that record might improve. ''I just hate to
waste the real good pitching performances we've had of late because
our hitting has been spotty,'' Baylor said. ... SS Ricky Gutierrez,
on the DL since May 25 with a separated right shoulder, would like
to return this week, but he doesn't know if that will happen. ''I
haven't thrown or hit yet,'' Gutierrez said. ''I'll see by this
week how far I am. I really don't have a timetable.''
</P>
