<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS Debate Underway on Peru  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- A resolution to investigate Peru's
electoral process but not to sanction the South American nation was
winning support Monday evening from most foreign ministers at a
conference of the Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   The organization of 34 Western Hemisphere nations met for a
second day Monday and focused on Peru, where President Alberto
Fujimori was re-elected May 28 in a runoff vote that featured
himself as the only candidate. His opponent boycotted the runoff,
alleging the election was rigged, and independent monitors refused
to observe the vote because it failed to meet basic international
standards of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution being considered by the OAS on Monday was
authored by host Canada. It stops short of any sanctions against
Peru, but notes that problems in the voting that re-elected
Fujimori tainted the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   Debate by the OAS general assembly began after two days of
back-room negotiations that pitted Peru and some Latin American
allies that oppose foreign intervention in election issues against
the United States and others seeking a harsh response to
irregularities in the Peruvian voting.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian Foreign Minister Fernando de Trazegnies earlier said
wording that questioned the result of the vote would be dropped
from the resolution. But the draft proposed for debate includes a
reference to concerns that the outcome's credibility had been
undermined by ''persistent reports of irregularities.''
</P>
<P>
   Most foreign ministers said they supported the proposal as a
strong step to confront a weakening of democracy in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ''Latin America as a whole is affected by any backsliding with
respect to democracy by any of our countries,'' said Marie Alvear
of Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Rangel, however, said the
resolution amounted to unwanted intervention and lacked the
consensus of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''One cannot harm or affect democracy on behalf of democracy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed resolution orders an investigative mission of two --
OAS Secretary General Cesar Gaviria of Colombia and Canadian
Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy -- to leave for Peru
''immediately'' to work on ways to strengthen democracy there.
Specific issues to be studied include reforming the electoral
process and bolstering freedom of the press, the proposal says.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was likely to disappoint human rights groups that
wanted the OAS to suspend Peru or otherwise pressure it to hold new
elections.
</P>
<P>
   A human rights report has accused the South American country of
failing to meet democratic election standards. Former President
Jimmy Carter joined two former Latin American leaders in an open
letter to the OAS meeting that also criticized the Peru election.
</P>
<P>
   Peru was the main issue of the second day of the OAS three-day
general assembly, following protests Sunday by free-trade activists
that led to 41 arrests and prompted overwhelming security measures.
</P>
<P>
   No protesters turned up at the downtown Windsor meeting site by
mid-afternoon Monday, probably due as much to cold, rainy weather
that descended on this southern Ontario city across the border from
Detroit as to the armed riot police patrolling downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   Outside an OAS luncheon elsewhere, scores of demonstrators
linked arms and sat down in the rain to block delegates from
entering. Police had to pick up some of the protesters to clear the
road. No arrests were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The protests Sunday were the largest in memory at an OAS
gathering and brought the grouping of 34 countries face-to-face
with the anti-free trade movement that disrupted a World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle in December and also evoked street
clashes at an International Monetary Fund meeting in Washington
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Organization of American States, http://www.oas.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
