<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockers 69, Sting 53  </HEADLINE>
By JENNA FRYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Eva Nemcova scored 16 points as the
Cleveland Rockers beat Charlotte 69-53 Monday night, the Sting's
eighth consecutive loss dating to last season.
</P>
<P>
   The game was never close for Charlotte (0-3), which was
outrebounded 38-23, had 18 turnovers and missed all 13 of its
3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Nemcova opened the game with a jumper and a 3-pointer, and
Merlakia Jones scored seven straight points to give the Rockers a
12-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (2-1) had a 19-7 lead with 10:56 to play in the first
half when Charlotte coach T.R. Dunn pulled his starters. The
reserves fared no better, though, and Cleveland pushed the score to
27-9 when Dunn sent guard Dawn Staley back in three minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland took a 40-17 lead into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockers took their largest lead of the game three minutes
into the second half when Suzie McConnell Serio hit a 3-pointer to
make it 47-21.
</P>
<P>
   The Sting then got a spark from Andrea Stinson, who scored five
straight points in a 10-0 run that made it 47-31 with 12:04 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte's Rhonda Mapp later made two jump shots and a free
throw in a 5-0 run that cut the score to 59-48 with 1:59 to play.
But Mapp missed a chance to pull the Sting within single digits
when her 3-point attempt bounced off the rim with 80 seconds to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland got the rebound and converted on Rushia Brown's layup
that made it 61-48 with 1:17 to play, sealing the win for the
Rockers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones added 11 points for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Mapp led the Sting with 17 points and Stinson added 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
