<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox 3, Marlins 2  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LONG
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Carl Everett hit a solo home run in the ninth
inning as the Boston Red Sox snapped their longest losing streak of
the season at five games with a 3-2 win over the Florida Marlins on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, a former Marlins player, entered the game as a
pinch-hitter in the seventh inning, hitting into a fielder's
choice. He stayed in the game, though, and got another at-bat with
one out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   He hit the first pitch from Ricky Bones (1-1) into the
right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield (2-4) allowed one hit and one walk in two innings
for the win. Derek Lowe pitched a perfect ninth inning for his 11th
save.
</P>
<P>
   The come-from-behind win spoiled another strong outing by
Marlins starter Reid Cornelius. Cornelius allowed six hits and one
run over 6 1-3 innings. He gave up one run in eight innings at
Pittsburgh last week.
</P>
<P>
   After Braden Looper gave up back-to-back hits to start the
eighth, Armando Almanza intentionally walked Nomar Garciaparra to
load the bases. After striking out Brian Daubach, Almanza walked
Jason Varitek to tie the game at 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins scored a pair of runs in the first inning on Cliff
Floyd's 10th home run of the season. Luis Castillo singled and
advanced to third on a stolen base and an error by Red Sox starter
Pete Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek had Castillo picked off at first, but his throw to
Brian Daubach was in the dirt. Two batters later, Floyd's hammered
Schourek's 3-2 pitch into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   But Schourek settled down after the shaky start, retiring 15 of
the next 17 batters before giving up a two-out double in the sixth
to Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Boston manger Jimy Williams lifted Schourek for Everett in the
seventh, and the move paid off two innings later.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek allowed five hits and two runs. He struck out three
without a walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox cut the lead in half with a run in the second
inning. Jason Varitek walked, moved to third on Manny Alexander's
double and scored on Donnie Sadler's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Strikeout leader Preston Wilson of the Marlins struck out
three times, giving him 79 this season. ... Castillo stole two
bases, giving him a major-league best 25 this season. ... Everett
has an 11-game hitting streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
