<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tipper Gore: Politics is Personal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORRIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Tipper Gore appealed for votes Monday for
her husband's Democratic presidential campaign in traditionally
Republican eastern Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   She stopped short of calling Al Gore's home state a battleground
in the November election against Republican George W. Bush but
reminded her audience that ''politics is personal.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to leave you with a thought, particularly in East
Tennessee where every single vote is critically important,'' she
told about 250 Anderson County Democrats who came despite heavy
rain.
</P>
<P>
   ''When John Kennedy ran for election in 1960, after everything
was said and done, they went back and counted the votes. And do you
know he won by one vote per precinct? Just one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''So take that message to young people, veterans, women, people
that we work with, ... people that think their voice doesn't matter
or their vote isn't going to count.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently said he has a ''pretty good chance'' of carrying
the state in November.
</P>
<P>
   A Mason-Dixon poll conducted in March showed Gore with 47
percent support in Tennessee, to Bush's 41 percent, with a margin
of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance earlier in the day at Erma Siegel Elementary
School in Murfreesboro, Mrs. Gore said that, if elected, her
husband will put more mental health professionals in schools and
get teachers trained to recognize mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   She said he also will seek better insurance coverage for mental
illness treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
