<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles 4, Mets 2  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Albert Belle, playing his first game at Shea
Stadium, had three hits and drove in two runs as the Baltimore
Orioles beat the New York Mets 4-2 on a windy Monday night and
broke a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Tyner, playing his first game in the big leagues, was
2-for-3 for New York, including an RBI single off Mike Mussina. The
23-year-old rookie was promoted from Triple-A Norfolk before the
game and immediately became the Mets' leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles manager Mike Hargrove, back after missing two games
while attending his son's high school graduation in Cleveland, made
an unusual move that paid off during a three-run rally in the
seventh off Mike Hampton (6-5).
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who had won four straight decisions, gave up a leadoff
homer to B.J. Surhoff that made it 2-all in the seventh. Mark Lewis
followed with a single and Mussina, allowed to bat, bunted into a
forceout at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Amaral walked and, with Mussina at second, Hargrove sent in
Delino DeShields to run for the pitcher. Mike Bordick delivered a
single to center field that scored the speedy DeShields -- Mussina
likely would not have made it.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Belle blooped an RBI double for a 4-2 lead that
finished Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Mussina (3-6) gave up two runs in the second, ending the inning
by getting Mike Piazza on a fly ball with the bases loaded. Mussina
allowed little else before leaving after the sixth, retiring his
last nine batters.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's bid for a solo home run in the eighth was knocked back
in play by the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Timlin pitched the ninth for his fifth save. Orioles
pitched retired their final 18 batters.
</P>
<P>
   Tyner, batting .347 at Norfolk and leading the International
League with 27 stolen bases, was New York's first-round draft pick
in 1998. Called up earlier in the day, the left fielder made a fast
impression with the Mets, too.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the bottom of the first, he hit a one-hopper off
Mussina's glove and beat third baseman Cal Ripken's throw for a
single. Tyner's try at stealing second was foiled when Derek Bell
hit a foul ball.
</P>
<P>
   Bell then grounded into a forceout at second base, but Tyner
hustled and slid into Bordick, forcing a wild throw.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the second, Tyner sliced an opposite-field
single to left for a 1-0 lead. Edgardo Alfonzo later drew a
bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   Belle hit a single in the third that drove in Amaral, who scored
twice and stole two bases.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Tyner was flawless in the field. The Mets hope he can fill
the leadoff spot left when Rickey Henderson was released last
month. ... RHP Rick Reed will start Tuesday night for the Mets. He
missed his last start because of an injured side muscle. ... The
Orioles improved to 10-22 on the road. They were coming off a
three-game sweep at Montreal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
