<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY Council Urges NRA Not Open Shop  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The City Council on Monday urged the National
Rifle Association not to open a theme store and restaurant in Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA is currently negotiating to lease space for an eatery
tentatively called The N.R.A. Grille. An adjoining shop is to offer
virtual-reality trap and skeet shooting, outdoor clothing and
hunting accessories.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no plans for the store to sell guns, the idea
has gotten a cool reception since it was announced last month by
NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre.
</P>
<P>
   In its resolution Monday, the Council said, ''The promotion of
guns has no place in such an entertainment venture and especially
not in Times Square, where the city has worked hard to rid the area
of guns and gun-related violence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Powers, the NRA's director of public affairs, said the
vote would have no effect on the group's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the City Council of New York cannot stomach the fact that
40 million Americans participate in shooting sports, they will
choke on their own political correctness,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 2227 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
