<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands PM Taken Hostage  </HEADLINE>
By RAY LILLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- Rebels seized the prime minister
of the Solomon Islands on Monday on Guadalcanal, where U.S. Marines
first took the offensive against Japan after the attack on Pearl
Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Phone lines and air links to the Solomons were cut as the rebels
from a shadowy group calling itself the Malaita Eagle Force set up
roadblocks around Honiara, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Malaita Eagle gunmen demanded the resignation of Prime
Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu, and officials from the tiny South
Pacific nation met Tuesday to vote on a motion to oust him from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu had offered last week to resign as his support
dwindled, but the necessary government meeting never took place
because officials from around the sprawling island nation did not
arrive on time.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ulufa'alu was seized, the rebels asked him if he would
voluntarily resign, but he said he would prefer to see his
political fate determined through a government vote, said Brad
Tattersfield, a spokesman for the New Zealand Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The Malaita rebels overran police stations and the Government
Telecommunications Center in Honiara early Monday, Australian
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats in New Zealand said the rebels raided a police armory
in Honiara and stole weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent coup attempt was the second in the South Pacific in
weeks -- with armed rebels in Fiji still holding the deposed prime
minister and more than 30 other people seized in a raid on
Parliament on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Fiji's military chief said rebel leader George
Speight could play no role in any new government. Speight responded
that he was ready to keep his captives as long as necessary to get
his way.
</P>
<P>
   While the standoff on Fiji represented friction between the
majority indigenous Fijians represented by Speight and ethnic
Indians, the conflict on Guadalcanal -- the Solomon Islands main
island -- involved residents of different islands in the chain.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 18 months, the Malaita Eagle Force and another
rebel group, the Isatabu Freedom Movement, have been fighting on
Guadalcanal, where thousands of migrants from the nearby island of
Malaita live.
</P>
<P>
   Honiara is largely populated by Malaitans, including Ulufa'alu.
</P>
<P>
   The Isatabu force wants to push the Malaita migrants off
Guadalcanal, while the Malaita Eagle forces have resisted with
weapons dug up from World War II arms dumps on the island.
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 people have been killed or have disappeared in the
fighting between the islanders and 20,000 have been forced to flee
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent skirmish, the headless body of a rebel was left on
a street in Honiara.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Fiji's crisis, the entire government of the Solomon
Islands was not captured. The government was still functioning,
making it unclear whether a full blown crisis was unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the rebels, lawyer Andrew Nori, told a Solomon
Islands radio station, monitored by officials in Wellington, that
Prime Minister Ulufa'alu was being held at home in ''protective
custody'' after being captured by six Malaita group gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   But Australia's Foreign Minister, Alexander Downer, said he
understood Ulufa'alu was allowed to move freely about Honiari,
provided he did not stray from the Malaita gunmen who followed him.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Philip Reeker said 66
Peace Corps volunteers and four staff members are in the Solomons
but most are not living in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   In World War II, the Guadalcanal battle was the start of the
island-hopping campaign that led to the recapture of the
Philippines and the eventual defeat of Japan in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven-month battle, the Marines landed on Guadalcanal
Aug. 7, 1942, and the last Japanese soldier was not expelled until
Feb. 9, 1943.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomons are 2,230 miles northwest of Wellington and 1,600
miles northeast of Sydney, Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 2242 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
