<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers 2, Dodgers 0  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN HAWKINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Ryan Glynn, a Triple-A player called up
specifically for the start, won a duel against $105 million pitcher
Kevin Brown as the Texas Rangers beat the Los Angeles Dodgers 2-0
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn (1-0) was promoted from Oklahoma to start in place of
Darren Oliver and allowed two hits in eight shutout innings,
striking out six. John Wetteland finished to convert his 13th
consecutive save chance, his 16 in 19 opportunities overall.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than enough to beat Brown (4-2), who allowed five
hits in his second complete game. He walked none and struck out a
season-high nine.
</P>
<P>
   Texas went ahead in the sixth when Mike Lamb singled and scored
on Jason McDonald's broken-bat double with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer doubled leading off the seventh and scored on David
Segui's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Brown faced the minimum 15 batters in the first five innings and
didn't allow a ball out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn started slowly, giving up consecutive walks with two outs
in the first. He then struck out Eric Karros, starting a stretch in
which he retired 13 of his next 14 -- the only runner reaching on
Lamb's error at third base.
</P>
<P>
   He carried a no-hitter into the sixth before F.P. Santangelo, a
.141 hitter, had a leadoff single to center only to be thrown out
trying to steal second base.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek then hit another single back up the middle and
Shawn Green walked with two outs in the sixth before Karros ended
another threat by striking out.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, 2-3 in 11 starts, skipped his turn in the rotation after
complaining of having a tired arm in each of his last two outings.
Glynn is likely to be spent to back Triple-A, and Oliver could
return to face Colorado on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown started his major league career with the Ranger. When he
took the mound for the first inning, the song ''Money'' blared over
the stadium speakers. Brown signed a record $105 million,
seven-year contract with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Brown has 68 complete games in his career. ... AL MVP Ivan
Rodriguez took most of the night off after manager Johnny Oates
gave him the option of taking Monday or Wednesday off. Bill
Haselman got his eighth start in 56 games this season, but was
replaced in the ninth after Haselman was lifted for a pinch runner.
... Glynn had to step off the mound momentarily with two outs in
the fifth when the crowd erupted in cheers. The Dallas Stars hockey
team had just scored a goal in Game 4 of the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
