<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Support for Japanese Govt. Falls  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The public support rate for the Cabinet of Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori plummeted to 17 percent in May with the
disapproval rating surging to 66 percent, a newspaper poll
published Tuesday showed.
</P>
<P>
   The poll in Japan's top economic daily, the Nihon Keizai
Shimbun, was the latest survey to show Mori's government plunging
in popularity ahead of June 25 lower house elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Nihon Keizai cited Mori's recent comment calling Japan a
''divine nation with the emperor at the center'' as being
especially damaging. Critics have linked the comment to the
emperor-worship of Japan's wartime past.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll, conducted from Friday through Sunday,
questioned 3,000 eligible voters nationwide, of whom 60 percent
gave a valid response. No margin of error was given.
</P>
<P>
   The disapproval rating of 66 percent was double that registered
in a Nihon Keizai poll in April. The support rating of 17 percent
was less than half of that in the previous poll.
</P>
<P>
   As in other recent polls, the Nihon Keizai survey showed doubts
about Mori's capacity to lead. Among those who do not support
Mori's Cabinet, 60 percent said they do not trust Mori, and 50
percent said he lacks leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The voter discontent, however, may not be enough to topple the
ruling three-party coalition, led by Mori's Liberal Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP continued to win the highest support with a rating of
37.5 percent, marking a 5 percentage point drop from the previous
poll. All the opposition parties received higher ratings compared
with the April survey, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Mori took office on April 5 after then-Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi suffered a stroke. Since then, Mori has faced a string of
scandals and criticism that he is weak on policy. Obuchi died on
May 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
