<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji's Ruler Says No More Grants  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Fiji's military ruler said Tuesday that the
rebels holding government hostages in parliament won't be getting
any additional concessions and should accept an amnesty offer to
end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Commodore Frank Bainimarama also warned army reservists who are
holed up in Fiji's parliamentary compound with George Speight's
rebels to come out or lose their salaried commissions. Less than a
dozen reservists are believed to be inside.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not take any more demands,'' Bainimarama told a news
conference. ''We are requesting them to release the hostages,
return arms and in return, we will grant them amnesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bainimarama said Speight's wish for a system that will give
indigenous Fijians greater rights than the nation's ethnic Indian
minority ''will be reflected in the constitution.'' He would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has indicated he is willing to hold onto his more than
30 hostages -- including deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry,
the first Indian to hold that office -- for as long as it takes to
get his way.
</P>
<P>
   But talks between the two sides have broken down and there was
no sign when they might resume.
</P>
<P>
   Fijian police held a funeral at their barracks in the capital of
Suva on Tuesday for an officer who was the only person killed in
the crisis. Speight supporters shot Filipo Seavula during street
fighting May 28.
</P>
<P>
   Bainimarama has ruled out the use of force to try to free the
captives. Speight says such a move would lead to the hostages being
executed by his rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The military also hinted Tuesday that it is willing to let the
crisis go on indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Bainimarama urged residents to go about their daily lives with
as much normalcy as possible in Fiji, 2,250 miles northeast of
Sydney, Australia. He said this can happen even if Speight remains
inside parliament with his gunmen and the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Bainimarama declared martial law and took charge of Fiji on May
29 after the crisis had dragged on for more than a week. He
disputed Speight's suggestions that the military was hoping to hang
onto power.
</P>
<P>
   ''They keep saying we want to be the government,'' Bainimarama
said. ''That's one of the issues they keep harping about. We don't
want to be the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 2341 </TRAILER>
