<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pistons Replace Sund With Dumars  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons have selected Joe
Dumars, a member of the ''Bad Boys'' teams that won NBA
championships in 1989 and 1990, as head of basketball operations,
according to newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
   Dumars will replace Rick Sund, who will become an assistant to
Dumars, The Detroit News said in Tuesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons have called a news conference for 4 p.m. Tuesday at
which they are expected to name interim coach George Irvine as
their permanent coach. Dumars' appointment is to be made at the
same time, according to the News and Detroit Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   Dumars, 37, is getting a four-year deal with the Pistons, the
Free Press said.
</P>
<P>
   The first job for Dumars would be to retain the services of
Grant Hill, who becomes a free agent July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not like I just started working here,'' Dumars told the
Free Press on Monday. ''Grant and I talk all the time. We have
known each other since his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I haven't developed a relationship with him over the past
six years that can stand on its own merits, then I've been doing
something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Irvine's appointment, Dumars said: ''I know what
people think. Why not a bigger name coach? But a big name coach
only means he did something big someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumars played for the Pistons from 1985-99. He became vice
president for basketball operations in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
