<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pistons Set To Sign Irvine  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY ATKINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- George Irvine changed his mind. Now
the Detroit Pistons must hope they get lucky with Grant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons are expected to announce Tuesday that Irvine has
signed to coach for the next three years. They were also to
announce the promotion of former star Joe Dumars to head of
basketball operations, The Detroit News and the Detroit Free Press
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He was appointed interim coach after the Pistons fired Alvin
Gentry in March. The team was 14-10 under Irvine, who was endorsed
by Hill and Jerry Stackhouse, the club's leading scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after taking over from Gentry, Irvine said he wasn't
interested in the head coaching job again. But by the time the
season ended, with a first-round playoff loss, it was apparent
Irvine was reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   Irvine agreed to a deal last Friday that could pay him up to
$5.2 million, starting with a $1.5 million salary during the
2000-01 season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that is small change compared with what the Pistons are
prepared to offer Hill, who will become a free agent July 1.
</P>
<P>
   As a player with six years experience, the Pistons can offer
Hill the league maximum of $86.6 million. That's based on a
starting salary of $9 million, with annual raises of $1.12 million.
That would give him a salary of $15.7 million in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who is making $7.5 million this season, could do even
better by signing a one-year deal with Detroit, then becoming a
free agent again.
</P>
<P>
   Under that scenario, Hill would sign a one-year contract to play
for the Pistons next season at $9 million. Then, in August of 2001,
he could sign a seven-year deal, starting at $11 million, which
would pay him $105.875 million.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Pistons are prepared to pay Hill about $115
million over the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   If the Pistons can convince Hill to remain in Detroit, it
obviously would make Irvine's job a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old coach came to the Pistons two years ago from the
Indiana Pacers where he worked 16 seasons, primarily as vice
president of basketball operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-05-00 2353 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
